2) The full bucket classification

A. Scan / array / string control buckets

1. Two Pointers

What it means:
Use two indices moving through data with a relationship between them.

Typical use:
	•	sorted arrays
	•	pair finding
	•	in-place partitioning
	•	palindrome checks
	•	linked list runner techniques

Common composites:
	•	Sorting + Two Pointers
	•	Two Pointers + Dummy Node
	•	Opposite Pointers
	•	Fast/Slow Pointers

Why it overlaps:
Two pointers is usually a movement style, not the whole strategy.

⸻

2. Sliding Window

What it means:
Maintain a valid moving subarray / substring while extending and shrinking bounds.

Typical use:
	•	longest/shortest valid substring
	•	fixed-size window stats
	•	distinct element constraints
	•	frequency-controlled substrings

Common composites:
	•	Sliding Window + Hash Map
	•	Sliding Window + Hash Set
	•	Binary Search on Answer + Sliding Window

Why it overlaps:
Sliding window often needs:
	•	Hash Map / Set for frequencies
	•	Counting
	•	Two Pointers underneath

⸻

3. Prefix Sum

What it means:
Precompute cumulative information so interval queries become O(1) or easier.

Typical use:
	•	subarray sum
	•	range totals
	•	balance / difference problems
	•	parity / remainder counting
	•	2D rectangle sums

Common composites:
	•	Prefix Sum + Hash Map
	•	Prefix Sum + Sorting
	•	Prefix Sum + Binary Search
	•	Difference Array + Prefix Sum

Why it overlaps:
Prefix sum is usually a helper trick, not a complete algorithm by itself.

