The anatomy of a good LeetCode drawing

Across the whole source, the best drawings almost always follow the same structure:

1. Pick the base canvas

Choose one of these first:
	•	strip
	•	grid
	•	node-link tree/list
	•	bucket table
	•	container
	•	chart
	•	formula board

That is the surface where the algorithm lives.

2. Add anchors

Every good drawing marks the “fixed objects”:
	•	indices
	•	nodes
	•	rows/columns
	•	buckets
	•	states
	•	intervals
	•	current max/min
	•	carry / visited / count

Without anchors, the drawing becomes decorative instead of explanatory.

3. Add motion

Then show what changes:
	•	pointers move
	•	window expands/shrinks
	•	frontier spreads
	•	node links change
	•	stack pushes/pops
	•	counts increment/decrement
	•	recurrence arrows feed new cells

Motion is what turns a static picture into an algorithm.

4. Add the invariant

The source repeatedly uses a tiny side note to show:
	•	what must stay true
	•	what gets updated
	•	what triggers action

Examples:
	•	“map count hit 0”
	•	“L1 <= R2 and L2 <= R1”
	•	“carry moves to next column”
	•	“visited set prevents repeats”
	•	“dp[i] depends on dp[i-1], dp[i-2]”

This is usually the single most important label in the whole diagram.

5. Add the complexity overlay

The guide’s row structure separates algorithm drawing from complexity drawing, but visually the usual overlays are:
	•	nested loop fan-out
	•	recursion tree width/depth
	•	table size
	•	container size
	•	number of passes
	•	extra buffer or memo size

So every strong diagram really has two layers:
	•	how the algorithm moves
	•	why its cost is what it is

The fastest way to choose a draw bucket from a new question

Use this decision order:
	1.	Is the data naturally 2D?
Draw a grid / board.
	2.	Are you rewiring or traversing nodes?
Draw a node-link canvas.
	3.	Are you querying remembered facts or counts?
Draw lookup-table / buckets.
	4.	Are you mostly scanning one sequence?
Draw a strip / timeline / pointer.
	5.	Is the key state a stack, queue, heap, or deque?
Draw a container.
	6.	Is the core logic recurrence or memo?
Draw a state table.
	7.	Is the main insight numeric/invariant-based?
Draw a formula / invariant board.
	8.	Is it really about subset bits, ranges, or powers-of-two jumps?
Draw a range / bit-state canvas.
	9.	Is it SQL/tabular?
Draw a relational table.
	10.	Is the process hidden inside an object/buffer/API?
Draw an object / process canvas.

The practical master rule

For almost every row in your source, a usable drawing can be built as:

Canvas + Anchors + Motion + Invariant

Examples:
	•	Strip + [L,R] + shrink/expand + “window valid”
	•	Buckets + counts + add/remove + “need count == 0”
	•	Grid + blocked cells + frontier wave + “distance layer”
	•	List nodes + dummy/current + rewiring + “tail always correct”
	•	DP table + recurrence arrows + fill order + “state reused”

That is the real anatomy underneath the whole guide.

