6) Container bucket

Use when the state is the contents of stack, queue, deque, or heap.

Brute Force Method

Usually:
	•	rescan to find next best
	•	simulate with expensive list operations
	•	recompute max/min from scratch
	•	repeatedly search pending items

BF Complexity Vis.

Metaphor:
	•	every operation searches the whole pile
	•	order is maintained manually and painfully

How to Draw BF

Draw:
	•	unsorted bag of pending items
	•	repeated search arrows for best element
	•	or repeated linear scans of current state

Optimised Pattern

Usually:
	•	Monotonic Stack
	•	Queue/Deque
	•	Priority Queue / Heap
	•	Two-stack simulation
	•	BFS queue

Opt Vis. Technique

The metaphor is:
	•	“the structure keeps order for you”
	•	“top/front always means something”
	•	“best item is exposed”

Dry Run (Opt)

Show:
	•	push
	•	pop
	•	enqueue/dequeue
	•	extract-min/max
	•	lazy transfer between structures

How to Draw (Opt)

Best template:
	•	draw the structure itself
	•	top/front/back clearly labeled
	•	current incoming item visible
	•	popped/removed item highlighted

Opt Complexity Vis.

Metaphor:
	•	each item enters once and leaves once
	•	or each operation touches logarithmic structure height

Draw Opt Complexity

Draw:
	•	stream entering stack/queue/heap
	•	note one push and one pop max per item
	•	heap as shallow tree if needed

Mem Vis (BF)

Memory picture:
	•	bloated temporary pending lists
	•	repeatedly rebuilt orderings

Mem Vis (Opt)

Memory picture:
	•	one explicit container
	•	exactly the active unresolved items
	•	memory proportional to structure size

