Yes — the deepest way to distinguish these is:

they are not six names for the same thing.
They are six different axes for describing one LeetCode question.

A clean mental model is:
	1.	Data Structure = the world the problem lives in
	2.	Pattern / Algorithm = the main engine that moves through that world
	3.	Variation = the specific subtype of that engine
	4.	Composite Type = the second engine / helper needed to make it work
	5.	Canonical Link = the prototype problem it most resembles
	6.	Complexity = the budget the final design must satisfy

That is the distinction.

⸻

The master distinction

1) Data Structure

What it defines

What is holding the data?
This is the shape of the input space.

Examples:
	•	String
	•	Array
	•	Linked List
	•	Matrix
	•	Binary Tree
	•	Graph
	•	Trie
	•	Interval list

What it does not define

It does not tell you the solution by itself.

Example:
	•	A string problem might use:
	•	Sliding Window
	•	DP
	•	Rolling Hash
	•	Trie
	•	Two Pointers
	•	A binary tree problem might use:
	•	DFS
	•	BFS
	•	Tree DP
	•	Binary Search on tree properties

So “String” is not a strategy. It is just the terrain.

Diagnostic question

What physical form is the input given in?

Best metaphor

Skeleton / terrain / container

Examples
	•	s = "abcabcbb" → String
	•	root with left/right children → Binary Tree
	•	grid[m][n] → Matrix
	•	edges list / adjacency list → Graph

⸻

2) Pattern / Algorithm

What it defines

What is the main engine?
This is the primary way you process the data.

Examples:
	•	Sliding Window
	•	BFS
	•	DFS
	•	Dynamic Programming
	•	Binary Search
	•	Greedy
	•	Two Pointers
	•	Hashing
	•	Heap
	•	Union-Find

What it does not define

It does not define the input shape.

Example:
	•	BFS can be used on:
	•	graphs
	•	trees
	•	grids
	•	implicit state spaces
	•	Sliding Window usually lives on:
	•	arrays
	•	strings
but that still does not tell you the exact subtype.

So pattern is the engine, not the terrain.

Diagnostic question

What is the main mathematical/process strategy that solves this?

Best metaphor

Engine / muscle / protocol

Examples
	•	“Find shortest path in a grid” → BFS
	•	“Find longest substring without repeating chars” → Sliding Window
	•	“Find minimum coins” → DP
	•	“Find target in sorted array” → Binary Search

⸻

3) Variation

What it defines

Which subtype of the main engine is this?
This is where one pattern splits into families.

Examples:
	•	Sliding Window
	•	Fixed-size
	•	Variable-size
	•	Variable-size + frequency constraint
	•	Binary Search
	•	Exact search
	•	First/last occurrence
	•	Search insert position
	•	Binary search on answer
	•	BFS
	•	Single-source
	•	Multi-source
	•	0-1 BFS
	•	DP
	•	1D DP
	•	2D grid DP
	•	Interval DP
	•	Bitmask DP
	•	Tree DP

What it does not define

Variation is not a new pattern.
It is a refined subtype of an existing pattern.

So:
	•	Variable Size Window is not separate from Sliding Window
	•	Multi-Source BFS is not separate from BFS
	•	Bitmask DP is not separate from DP

Diagnostic question

Which internal sub-form of this engine is being used?

Best metaphor

Mutation / sub-blade / subclass

Examples
	•	Longest substring with at most K distinct characters
	•	Pattern: Sliding Window
	•	Variation: Variable-size window
	•	Rotting Oranges
	•	Pattern: BFS
	•	Variation: Multi-source BFS
	•	Koko Eating Bananas
	•	Pattern: Binary Search
	•	Variation: Search on answer space

⸻

4) Composite Type

What it defines

Does the main engine need a second engine or helper?
This is the hybrid layer.

Examples:
	•	Sliding Window + Hash Map
	•	DFS + Memoization
	•	Binary Search + Greedy feasibility check
	•	Hash Map + Heap
	•	DP + Bitmask
	•	Tree DFS + Prefix Sum
	•	Union-Find + Sorting

What it does not define

Composite type is not the primary identity of the question.
It is the combination architecture.

Example:
	•	Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
	•	Pattern: Sliding Window
	•	Composite: + Hash Set / Hash Map
	•	Top K Frequent Elements
	•	Pattern could be seen as frequency selection
	•	Composite: Hash Map + Heap
	•	Koko Eating Bananas
	•	Pattern: Binary Search
	•	Composite: + feasibility function

So composite type answers:

What extra mechanism is necessary?

Diagnostic question

Can one engine solve it alone, or does it need a helper structure/check?

Best metaphor

Hybrid / boss-fight / second weapon

Examples
	•	Sliding Window + Hash Map
	•	Binary Search + Greedy
	•	DP + Memoization
	•	Hashing + Heap

⸻

5) Canonical Link

What it defines

Which pure prototype problem is this based on?
This is the educational lineage of the problem.

Examples:
	•	“Similar to Two Sum”
	•	“Same core invariant as Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters”
	•	“House Robber variant”
	•	“Number of Islands variant”
	•	“Climbing Stairs-style DP”
	•	“Koko-style answer-space binary search”

What it does not define

Canonical link is not the actual algorithm field.
It is the closest ancestor in the pattern family.

It tells you:
	•	what this problem is similar to
	•	what archetype to recall
	•	what mental prototype to transfer

Diagnostic question

If I had to teach this by saying “this is basically a variation of ___,” what goes in the blank?

Best metaphor

Prototype / ancestor / archetype

Examples
	•	Minimum Window Substring
	•	Canonical Link: Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
	•	House Robber II
	•	Canonical Link: House Robber
	•	01 Matrix
	•	Canonical Link: Rotting Oranges / Multi-source BFS family
	•	Partition Equal Subset Sum
	•	Canonical Link: 0/1 Knapsack

⸻

6) Complexity

What it defines

How fast and memory-efficient must the solution be?
This is the performance budget or final asymptotic profile.

Examples:
	•	O(N) time, O(1) space
	•	O(N log N) time, O(N) space
	•	O(V + E) time
	•	O(MN) time, O(MN) space
	•	O(2^N) for small constraints

What it does not define

Complexity is not the pattern.

Many different patterns can share the same complexity:
	•	Sliding Window → O(N)
	•	Hash Map scan → O(N)
	•	DFS tree traversal → O(N)
	•	BFS graph traversal → O(V+E)

And the same pattern can appear in different complexities depending on implementation:
	•	DP can be O(N), O(N^2), O(N^3), etc.
	•	Binary Search can be O(log N) or O(N log Answer) if each check costs O(N)

Diagnostic question

What runtime and space budget does the chosen design achieve or require?

Best metaphor

Physics / budget / cost model

