4. Sorting heuristics

Use sorting when it creates useful order.
	•	if pairing nearest/best candidates becomes easy after sorting
	•	if intervals become mergeable only after sorting
	•	if greedy correctness depends on processing in one order
	•	if two pointers only makes sense on sorted input
	•	if duplicates/grouping become contiguous after sort

Rule:
sort if it reveals structure you can exploit afterward.

⸻

5. Hashing heuristics

Use hashing when you need fast memory.
	•	existence lookup
	•	complement lookup
	•	frequency counts
	•	grouping by signature
	•	first/last seen index
	•	visited states
	•	deduplication

Rule:
if you keep asking “have I seen this?” or “how many of this?” use a map/set.

⸻

6. Sliding window heuristics

Use sliding window when all are true:
	•	data is linear
	•	target region is contiguous
	•	window validity can be updated incrementally
	•	left/right boundary movement is cheaper than restarting

Variations
	•	fixed-size window: exact k
	•	variable-size window: grow then shrink
	•	variable-size + counts: distinct chars / at most K / need map

Rule:
if you can maintain a property while moving two boundaries forward only, it is window-shaped.

Do not force sliding window when:
	•	validity depends on arbitrary nonlocal choices
	•	you cannot update the state incrementally when removing leftmost element

⸻

7. Two-pointers heuristics

Use two pointers when:
	•	data is sorted, or
	•	you compare from both ends, or
	•	you need slow/fast movement, or
	•	you are merging two ordered streams, or
	•	you need in-place compaction

Common forms:
	•	inward pinch
	•	same-direction chase
	•	fast/slow
	•	merge pointers

Rule:
two pointers works when relative pointer movement itself carries the logic.

⸻

8. Prefix-sum heuristics

Use prefix sum when:
	•	many subarray/range sums matter
	•	interval totals should become O(1)
	•	you can transform a condition on a subarray into a relation between two prefix states
	•	you want cumulative parity/remainder/balance

Rule:
if you keep recomputing totals over ranges, precompute cumulative state once.

Extension:
	•	prefix sum + hash map when you need target prefix differences
	•	2D prefix sum for rectangle sums

⸻

9. Binary-search heuristics

Binary search needs monotonicity somewhere.

Use standard binary search when:
	•	array is sorted
	•	or property flips from false to true across a boundary

Use answer-space binary search when:
	•	the data is not sorted, but candidate answers can be ordered
	•	feasibility of answer x implies feasibility/non-feasibility of larger/smaller answers

Typical clues:
	•	minimum speed
	•	smallest capacity
	•	largest minimum distance
	•	earliest feasible day
	•	maximize minimum / minimize maximum

Rule:
binary search is not about sorted arrays; it is about ordered search spaces with monotone decisions.

⸻

10. BFS heuristics

Use BFS when distance is “number of edges/steps/layers”.

Strong clues
	•	shortest path in unweighted graph/grid
	•	minimum operations
	•	nearest source
	•	level order traversal
	•	spread/rotting/fire/infection/wave

Variations
	•	single-source BFS
	•	multi-source BFS
	•	0-1 BFS
	•	level-order tree BFS

Rule:
BFS is for expanding evenly by distance layers.

⸻

11. DFS heuristics

Use DFS when:
	•	you need to fully explore a component/path/subtree
	•	connectivity / cycle / path existence matters
	•	recursion matches natural structure
	•	you need entry/exit logic around children

Typical clues:
	•	count components
	•	explore island
	•	validate tree shape
	•	subtree aggregation
	•	all paths
	•	deep choice tree

Rule:
DFS is for going deep, then returning with information.

⸻

12. Backtracking heuristics

Use backtracking when:
	•	you need all solutions or all valid constructions
	•	order/choice matters
	•	state can be modified and undone
	•	brute force is structurally correct but needs pruning

Typical clues:
	•	permutations
	•	combinations
	•	N-Queens
	•	Sudoku
	•	partition into valid groups

Rule:
backtracking = DFS over a choice tree with undo.

⸻

13. DP heuristics

Use DP when you see:
	•	overlapping subproblems
	•	repeated recursion
	•	optimal substructure
	•	“number of ways”
	•	“best value under constraints”
	•	prefix/suffix decision chains
	•	edit/transform/align two sequences
	•	interval splitting

Ask these 4 things
	•	What is the state?
	•	What is the transition?
	•	What are the base cases?
	•	In what order are states solved?

Common DP shapes
	•	1D DP
	•	2D DP
	•	grid DP
	•	string DP
	•	interval DP
	•	tree DP
	•	bitmask DP
	•	memoized DFS

Rule:
DP is justified when a hard problem becomes manageable once you name and reuse states.

⸻

14. Greedy heuristics

Use greedy when:
	•	a local choice can be proven safe
	•	sorted order reveals a dominant decision
	•	“take best now” simplifies the future without regret
	•	exchange argument or invariant feels plausible

Typical clues:
	•	interval scheduling
	•	lexicographic minimization
	•	assign resources optimally
	•	choose min/max immediate thing and continue

Rule:
greedy is correct only when local optimality preserves global optimality.

Red flag:
if you cannot explain why a local choice is safe, it may be DP instead.

⸻

15. Heap heuristics

Use heap when you repeatedly need:
	•	smallest/largest active element
	•	top K
	•	running median
	•	best next candidate among changing options
	•	schedule by current min/max priority

Rule:
heap is for dynamic extrema, not static sorting alone.

⸻

16. Stack / monotonic-stack heuristics

Use stack when:
	•	nested structure must be matched
	•	you need undo/reverse processing
	•	next greater/smaller element
	•	span/histogram/daily temperatures style boundary queries

Use monotonic stack when:
	•	elements are popped until an order invariant is restored
	•	nearest greater/smaller on left/right matters

Rule:
monotonic stack maintains an order invariant to answer boundary questions in linear time.

⸻

17. Union-find heuristics

Use DSU when:
	•	connectivity changes by merging edges/groups
	•	repeated “are these connected?” or “how many components?” queries matter
	•	graph structure is mostly about components, not path details

Typical clues:
	•	merge accounts
	•	redundant connection
	•	number of provinces
	•	dynamic island merging

Rule:
union-find is for connectivity maintenance, not path discovery.

⸻

18. Trie heuristics

Use trie when:
	•	prefix queries are central
	•	shared prefixes need efficient storage
	•	word search / dictionary matching
	•	bitwise trie for xor extrema

Rule:
trie is for prefix-structured search spaces.

⸻

19. Range-query heuristics

Use Fenwick / segment tree / sparse table when:
	•	many range queries and updates coexist
	•	prefix sums alone are too static or too limited
	•	queries are online / repeated
	•	you need range max/min/sum efficiently under updates

Rule:
once repeated range operations dominate, move from arrays to range structures.

⸻

20. Graph-advanced heuristics

Topological sort

Use when dependencies imply DAG order.
Clues:
	•	course schedule
	•	build order
	•	task prerequisites

Shortest path weighted

Use Dijkstra when edge weights are nonnegative.
Use Bellman-Ford/Floyd-Warshall only when problem size and weight behavior justify them.

Flow / matching

Use when allocation, bipartite pairing, capacity, or edge-disjoint/resource routing language appears.

Rule:
when the problem is really about relationships, convert it to graph form first.

⸻

21. Variation heuristics

After choosing the main engine, ask what subtype it is.

Sliding window
	•	fixed size if k is exact
	•	variable size if only condition is given
	•	add map/counts if distinct/frequency constraint exists

Binary search
	•	exact target
	•	left boundary / right boundary
	•	answer-space search
	•	search over rotated structure / partition logic

BFS
	•	single-source
	•	multi-source
	•	bidirectional BFS if two-end shortest search is large and symmetric
	•	0-1 BFS if weights are 0/1

DFS
	•	plain traversal
	•	recursion with return value
	•	memoized DFS
	•	backtracking DFS

DP
	•	1D
	•	2D
	•	interval
	•	tree
	•	bitmask
	•	digit DP
	•	memoized vs tabulated

Rule:
pattern first, variation second.

⸻

22. Composite heuristics

After selecting the main engine, ask whether it needs a helper.

Common composites
	•	sliding window + hash map
	•	prefix sum + hash map
	•	binary search + greedy check
	•	binary search + prefix sum / rolling hash
	•	DFS + memoization
	•	DP + bitmask
	•	greedy + sorting
	•	hash map + heap
	•	tree DFS + prefix accumulation
	•	BFS + visited set / state compression

Rule:
hard problems are often not new patterns; they are composites of known ones.

⸻

23. Canonical-link heuristics

Always ask:
What known prototype is this closest to?

Examples:
	•	Two Sum
	•	Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
	•	Minimum Window Substring
	•	Number of Islands
	•	Rotting Oranges
	•	House Robber
	•	Coin Change
	•	Climbing Stairs
	•	Merge Intervals
	•	Koko Eating Bananas
	•	Top K Frequent Elements
	•	LRU Cache

Rule:
recognition is faster when you map a new problem to an ancestor problem.

⸻

24. Brute-force-first heuristics

Before optimizing, state the brute force.

Why:
	•	reveals the search space
	•	shows the real bottleneck
	•	makes optimization justified instead of magical

Ask:
	•	what is the obvious exhaustive approach?
	•	what repeated work makes it slow?
	•	what memory or structure would avoid repetition?

Rule:
every strong optimized solution is a response to a specific brute-force bottleneck.

⸻

25. Bottleneck heuristics

Find the real cost center.
	•	repeated rescans → prefix sums / hashing / sorting / preprocessing
	•	repeated subproblems → DP / memoization
	•	repeated connectivity checks → union-find
	•	repeated min/max extraction → heap / monotonic structure
	•	repeated boundary searches → binary search / monotonic stack
	•	repeated whole-window validity checks → sliding window + counts

Rule:
optimize the repetition, not the syntax.

⸻

26. State heuristics

Every nontrivial problem needs a precise state description.

Ask:
	•	what minimum information determines “where I am”?
	•	what variables must be known to continue correctly?
	•	can the state be compressed?

Examples:
	•	index
	•	left/right boundaries
	•	current sum/count
	•	node + parent
	•	mask of used items
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	graph node + remaining budget

Rule:
if your state is fuzzy, your code will be buggy.

⸻

27. Invariant heuristics

Every good loop/structure has an invariant.

Examples:
	•	current window is valid
	•	stack is monotonic
	•	all items before i are processed
	•	heap top is best available choice
	•	dp states used for transition are already solved
	•	union-find parent pointers represent current components

Rule:
if you can state the invariant clearly, implementation becomes much safer.

⸻

28. Base-case heuristics

For recursion/DP:
	•	what is the smallest solvable input?
	•	what stops recursion?
	•	what states are known without transition?

Rule:
broken base cases usually create infinite recursion or corrupted DP.

⸻

29. Complexity heuristics

Use constraints to decide the maximum affordable complexity.

Also ask:
	•	is the cost dominated by states, transitions, edges, queries, or sorts?
	•	is hidden cost from copying strings/vectors/objects relevant?
	•	can space be reduced from table to rolling variables?

Rule:
budget drives architecture.

⸻

30. Memory heuristics

Ask:
	•	am I storing full paths, or can I store summaries?
	•	can I mutate in place safely?
	•	do I need visited/memo/state table, or am I duplicating work?
	•	does recursion depth risk stack overflow?

Rule:
make memory explicit; hidden memory is where many brute-force solutions die.

⸻

31. Drawing heuristics

Choose the right visual canvas.
	•	strip/timeline → arrays, strings, pointers, windows
	•	lookup table → hashing/counting
	•	grid/board → matrix BFS/DFS/2D DP
	•	node-link → trees, lists, tries
	•	chart/coordinate line → intervals, heights, geometry
	•	container drawing → stack/queue/heap
	•	state table → DP
	•	formula board → math/invariants
	•	graph network → graph/state machine
	•	object/process box → design/API/buffer problems

Rule:
pick the visual world that matches the state.

⸻

32. Interview heuristics

Use a communication sequence.
	•	understand inputs/outputs/edge cases
	•	match likely patterns
	•	plan brute force
	•	identify bottleneck
	•	propose optimized engine
	•	define state/invariant
	•	implement
	•	dry run
	•	evaluate time/space

Rule:
in interviews, clarity of diagnosis matters almost as much as the final code.

⸻

33. Study heuristics

To actually learn the system:
	•	do not memorize 3000 problems individually
	•	learn canonical families first
	•	revisit problems by spaced repetition
	•	interleave patterns, do not only binge one family
	•	after 15–20 minutes stuck, study solution, then re-derive it from memory
	•	keep a pattern/error log
	•	practice categorization without coding sometimes

Rule:
you retain patterns by repeated recognition and reconstruction, not passive reading.

⸻

34. “Don’t get trapped” heuristics
	•	shortest path does not always mean plain BFS; weighted cases change it
	•	sorted input does not force binary search; greedy/two pointers may dominate
	•	DP is not required just because recursion exists
	•	hashing is not always enough if ordering/ranking is central
	•	greedy is suspicious until proven safe
	•	backtracking is only acceptable when constraints allow explosion
	•	binary search requires monotonicity, not vibes

⸻

35. The master heuristic stack

When you open a new problem, run this order:
	1.	Translate the prompt
	2.	Read constraints
	3.	Identify data shape
	4.	Identify goal type
	5.	State brute force
	6.	Find the bottleneck
	7.	Pick primary engine
	8.	Pick variation
	9.	Add composite helper if needed
	10.	Name the state
	11.	State the invariant
	12.	Estimate complexity
	13.	Link to a canonical prototype
	14.	Choose a drawing canvas
	15.	Implement and dry run

That is the full heuristic operating system.

