4. The deep engine model

All patterns become easier if you stop treating them as labels and start treating them as ways of killing repetition.

Sliding Window

Kills repeated rescans of contiguous regions by maintaining a live interval.

Two Pointers

Kills nested pair scans when pointer motion can encode monotone progress.

Prefix Sum

Kills repeated range-total computation by moving work to preprocessing.

Hashing

Kills repeated lookup/frequency work by making memory explicit.

BFS

Kills repeated shortest-step search by expanding in distance layers.

DFS

Kills vague graph/tree exploration by giving a disciplined deep traversal.

Backtracking

Turns exhaustive search into a structured choice tree with undo.

Dynamic Programming

Kills repeated subproblems by naming and caching states.

Greedy

Kills future branching by proving one local choice is always safe.

Binary Search

Kills large answer spaces by exploiting monotonicity.

Heap

Kills repeated best-element search in changing active sets.

Monotonic Stack

Kills repeated nearest-boundary searches with an order invariant.

Union-Find

Kills repeated connectivity recomputation through component maintenance.

Trie

Kills repeated prefix matching by sharing paths.

Range Structures

Kill repeated dynamic range queries and updates.

So the deepest way to think about patterns is:

A pattern is a machine for eliminating a specific kind of repeated waste.

That is much stronger than memorizing trigger words.

