Always visually mark what is bad:
	•	overlapping subproblems
	•	same cells revisited
	•	same pairs checked again
	•	same ranges rescanned
	•	same structure rebuilt
	•	huge empty memory
	•	giant temporary object
	•	giant recursion tree

So the BF drawing is not just “how the naive method works.”
It is:

how the naive method wastes time or memory

⸻

2. The universal BF drawing formula

For almost every question in the corpus, you can draw brute force using this template:

Step 1

Draw the input world.

Step 2

Draw one naive attempt.

Step 3

Duplicate that attempt many times.

Step 4

Show overlap/repetition.

Step 5

Write the complexity source beside it.

So the canonical formula is:

World + naive action + repetition + overlap + tally

That is the full BF drawing grammar.

⸻

3. The 12 brute-force drawing buckets

These are the main brute-force canvases that cover essentially the entire corpus.

⸻

Bucket 1 — Exhaustive strip scan

This is the biggest brute-force bucket for arrays and strings.

When to use

Use this when brute force tries:
	•	every subarray
	•	every substring
	•	every start/end pair
	•	every scan from each index
	•	every window separately

How to draw

Draw one long strip:
	•	array or string on top
	•	below it, many brackets or shorter strips
	•	each bracket is one candidate region

What to exaggerate
	•	stack many brackets underneath
	•	make the strip look dense
	•	show repeated rescans inside each bracket

Complexity shape

This bucket often proves:
	•	O(N^2) for enumerating all regions
	•	O(N^3) when each region is rechecked internally

Typical examples
	•	Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
	•	Longest Palindromic Substring
	•	Maximum Subarray
	•	subarray/subsubstring enumeration problems

Mental picture

A triangle or pyramid of intervals under a single line.

What the drawing should say

“I am checking too many contiguous regions, and many of them overlap heavily.”

⸻

Bucket 2 — Pairwise comparison canvas

This is for all-pairs / all-comparisons brute force.

When to use

Use this when brute force checks:
	•	every pair
	•	every interval vs every interval
	•	every point vs every other point
	•	every row vs every row
	•	every word vs every word

How to draw

Use one of two forms:

Form A: crossing pair lines
Draw items in a row and connect many pairs with arcs/lines.

Form B: comparison matrix
Draw rows and columns, and shade/check every cell pair.

What to exaggerate
	•	too many lines
	•	too many matrix cells
	•	symmetric redundancy
	•	dense crossing

Complexity shape

Usually:
	•	O(N^2)
	•	or O(N^2 * extra_check) if each pair needs more work

Typical examples
	•	Two Sum brute force
	•	Merge Intervals brute force
	•	Max Points on a Line brute force
	•	many duplicate/comparison problems

Mental picture

A dense web or full matrix.

What the drawing should say

“I am comparing everything to everything.”

⸻

Bucket 3 — Branching choice tree

This is the brute-force king for recursion, subsets, combinations, and backtracking.

When to use

Use this when brute force tries:
	•	every subset
	•	every permutation
	•	every combination
	•	every yes/no branch
	•	every recursive split
	•	every word break split
	•	every board placement

How to draw

Draw:
	•	one root
	•	branches at each level
	•	leaves at the bottom
	•	repeated or dead-end branches

What to exaggerate
	•	wide branching
	•	deep height
	•	leaves exploding
	•	overlapping repeated states if relevant

Complexity shape

Usually:
	•	2^N
	•	N!
	•	exponential branching trees

Typical examples
	•	Generate Parentheses
	•	N-Queens
	•	Word Break brute force
	•	permutation/subset families
	•	regex-style branching recursion

Mental picture

A giant recursive tree.

What the drawing should say

“The search space explodes because every choice creates more choices.”

⸻

Bucket 4 — Grid/board exhaustive exploration

This is for brute-force spatial search.

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	explores many paths in a grid
	•	restarts from many cells
	•	checks rows/cols/boxes repeatedly
	•	manually simulates board movement everywhere

How to draw

Draw the board:
	•	mark start points
	•	draw multiple path branches or repeated scans
	•	show the same cells being revisited from different directions

What to exaggerate
	•	ripple clutter
	•	many path branches
	•	repeated cell visits
	•	huge empty support board if memory is wasted

Complexity shape

Can show:
	•	exponential path branching
	•	O(MN * repeated_scan)
	•	repeated whole-board checks

Typical examples
	•	Word Search brute force
	•	Sudoku checks
	•	N-Queens naive placement
	•	path-sum grid branching
	•	flood-fill done redundantly

Mental picture

A crowded board with many arrows and dead ends.

What the drawing should say

“I am repeatedly re-entering the same spatial area or exploring too many paths.”

⸻

Bucket 5 — Graph/network repeated traversal

This is the brute-force canvas for general graphs.

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	runs BFS/DFS from every node
	•	checks connectivity repeatedly
	•	tries many paths
	•	explores every route separately

How to draw

Draw the graph once, then:
	•	redraw or overlay many traversal waves
	•	show searches starting again inside already-known regions
	•	show paths overlapping heavily

What to exaggerate
	•	repeated component scans
	•	repeated shortest-path attempts
	•	path overlap

Complexity shape

Often:
	•	O(N^2) on graph-size problems
	•	repeated O(V+E) traversals

Typical examples
	•	Minimum Height Trees brute force
	•	repeated component counting
	•	repeated shortest search from each candidate

Mental picture

A graph with too many traversal waves.

What the drawing should say

“I keep traversing the same network from scratch.”

⸻

Bucket 6 — Node-link rebuild / structure conversion

This is for linked lists, trees, and node structures where BF cheats by converting or rebuilding.

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	converts linked lists to arrays/integers
	•	dumps nodes into a bucket
	•	rebuilds structure from scratch
	•	sorts/serializes then reconstructs

How to draw

Draw the original structure:
	•	linked chains or nodes
	•	a funnel or bucket in the middle
	•	a rebuilt structure on the other side

What to exaggerate
	•	conversion overhead
	•	giant temporary object
	•	loss of native structure
	•	rebuild cost

Complexity shape

Often:
	•	extra copy/rebuild cost
	•	extra space
	•	wrong scaling due to conversion

Typical examples
	•	Add Two Numbers via integer conversion
	•	Merge Two Sorted Lists by dumping/sorting/rebuilding
	•	tree/list serialization-style brute force

Mental picture

A funnel and rebuild pipeline.

What the drawing should say

“I am ignoring the native structure and rebuilding everything.”

⸻

Bucket 7 — Relational row-by-row scan

This is the brute-force canvas for SQL/pandas-style questions.

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	compares every row with every row
	•	manually joins tables by scanning all rows
	•	repeatedly rescans for group summaries
	•	ranks rows by full comparisons

How to draw

Draw tables:
	•	rows and columns
	•	many cross-table arrows
	•	repeated scans of the same rows
	•	bloated intermediate tables

What to exaggerate
	•	cartesian feel
	•	repeated full-table search
	•	manual row matching
	•	giant intermediate results

Complexity shape

Usually:
	•	nested row scans
	•	repeated grouping/rescanning

Typical examples
	•	join problems done without keyed matching
	•	grouped summary by repeated scans
	•	ranking done row-by-row

Mental picture

A table full of crossing lines.

What the drawing should say

“I am matching or grouping rows the hard way.”

⸻

Bucket 8 — Number / bit / arithmetic brute simulation

This is for numeric problems where BF tests cases or converts representations naively.

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	checks many integers one by one
	•	converts huge digit arrays to one number
	•	tests divisors/candidates naively
	•	counts bits for each number from scratch
	•	simulates arithmetic case-by-case

How to draw

Use:
	•	number line
	•	binary boxes
	•	digit columns
	•	conversion funnels
	•	repeated candidate checks

What to exaggerate
	•	one-by-one numeric stepping
	•	overflow-prone conversion
	•	repeated bit counting
	•	repeated arithmetic checks

Complexity shape

Usually:
	•	linear over huge numeric ranges
	•	O(N * bits)
	•	repeated formula simulation

Typical examples
	•	Count primes naive checks
	•	Counting Bits naive bit counting
	•	Plus One via huge-number conversion
	•	range AND by checking every number

Mental picture

A number line or conversion machine.

What the drawing should say

“I am simulating arithmetic directly instead of exploiting structure.”

⸻

Bucket 9 — Interval / geometry pairwise canvas

This is the brute-force shape for overlap, span, and geometry problems.

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	checks every interval pair
	•	checks every point pair/triple
	•	compares all spans
	•	tests all line constructions

How to draw

Draw:
	•	intervals on a timeline
	•	points on a plane
	•	many pair connections
	•	shaded overlap regions

What to exaggerate
	•	dense overlap checks
	•	all-pairs geometry
	•	repeated span comparisons

Complexity shape

Usually:
	•	O(N^2)
	•	or worse with deeper checks

Typical examples
	•	Merge Intervals brute force
	•	Meeting Rooms brute force
	•	Max Points on a Line brute force

Mental picture

A timeline or point cloud full of pair lines.

What the drawing should say

“I am doing geometric all-pairs reasoning.”

⸻

Bucket 10 — Container / process simulation

This is for brute force that repeatedly moves items through queues/stacks/heaps or simulates process flow inefficiently.

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	manually moves all items between containers
	•	reorders the whole structure every operation
	•	simulates each step literally
	•	replays process state from scratch

How to draw

Draw:
	•	queue/stack/heap boxes
	•	arrows showing too much movement
	•	objects jumping between containers

What to exaggerate
	•	unnecessary shuffling
	•	repeated transfers
	•	extra buffer movement

Complexity shape

Usually:
	•	per-operation linear reshuffling
	•	repeated simulation cost

Typical examples
	•	Stack via queues naive transfers
	•	circular queue naive shifting
	•	process/state simulation problems

Mental picture

A machine with too many moving parts.

What the drawing should say

“I am physically moving too much state every time.”

⸻

Bucket 11 — Object / API / system brute simulation

This is for design, async, JS, or system-style questions where BF is “just simulate everything.”

When to use

Use this when brute force:
	•	rebuilds internal state per operation
	•	copies full objects repeatedly
	•	waits/schedules inefficiently
	•	creates excessive temporary objects

How to draw

Draw:
	•	object boxes
	•	API calls entering
	•	full internal rebuild each call
	•	giant temporary buffers

What to exaggerate
	•	repeated object allocation
	•	callback buildup
	•	buffer duplication
	•	whole-system mutation

Complexity shape

Often:
	•	too much per operation
	•	hidden memory explosion
	•	unnecessary system churn

Mental picture

A box with too much stuff happening inside it.

What the drawing should say

“I am simulating the whole machine instead of maintaining only the needed state.”

⸻

Bucket 12 — Miscellaneous exact brute-force canvas

This is the catch-all for exact one-off named BF visuals.

Some problems use special drawings that are still brute-force in spirit:
	•	giant case trees
	•	ugly hand-coded decision ladders
	•	exhaustive generated object lists
	•	fully materialized transformed states

The rule here is:
if it does not fit the standard buckets cleanly, still draw:
	•	the full candidate space,
	•	repeated checking,
	•	and the waste source.

⸻

4. The deepest rule for BF drawing

A brute-force drawing must answer three questions visually:

1. What candidates am I trying?

subarrays, paths, subsets, pairs, rows, states, operations

2. Why are there too many of them?

quadratic web, exponential tree, dense board, repeated scans

3. Where is the waste?

overlap, restart, rescanning, rebuilding, duplicated checks, extra memory

If your BF drawing shows only the algorithm but not the waste, it is incomplete.

⸻

5. The universal BF style guide

Rule 1 — Make it ugly on purpose

Optimized drawings should feel clean.
Brute-force drawings should feel visibly inefficient.

Rule 2 — Show repetition, not just one example

One subarray is not brute force.
A pyramid of subarrays is brute force.

Rule 3 — Show overlap

Repeated work is the entire reason optimization exists.

Rule 4 — Add a counting side-note

Write:
	•	N^2
	•	N^3
	•	2^N
	•	N!
	•	M x N
	•	“repeat from every node”
	•	“scan whole table again”

Rule 5 — Show memory waste separately if needed

Examples:
	•	new array created every time
	•	giant intermediate integer
	•	copied substrings
	•	path list per branch
	•	queue/object duplicated

Rule 6 — Keep the world recognizable

Use the same base terrain as the real problem:
	•	arrays stay strips
	•	trees stay node-link
	•	grids stay boards
	•	tables stay tables

Do not switch worlds unnecessarily.

⸻

6. How to choose the right BF drawing bucket fast

Use this decision tree:

If brute force checks every contiguous piece

Draw Strip / bracket exhaustive scan

If brute force checks every pair

Draw Pairwise comparison / matrix

If brute force tries every choice sequence

Draw Branching choice tree

If brute force explores many spatial paths

Draw Grid / board exhaustive exploration

If brute force reruns traversal across a graph

Draw Graph / network repeated traversal

If brute force converts or rebuilds linked structure

Draw Node-link rebuild / structure conversion

If brute force manually joins/groups rows

Draw Relational row-by-row scan

If brute force tests numbers/representations directly

Draw Number / bit / arithmetic simulation

If brute force repeatedly compares spans/overlaps

Draw Interval / geometry pairwise canvas

If brute force repeatedly shuffles containers/process state

Draw Container / process simulation

⸻

7. What to write beside the BF drawing

Every brute-force drawing should have a 1-line caption in this form:

Formula

“For every X, try every Y, and for each one do Z.”

Examples:
	•	“For every start index, try every end index, then rescan the whole substring.”
	•	“For every pair of intervals, check overlap.”
	•	“From each cell, branch into all valid paths.”
	•	“Generate every permutation, then validate each result.”
	•	“For each row, scan the whole other table again.”

This sentence is the textual DNA of the BF picture.

⸻

8. The single best BF drawing template

For any problem, fill this in:

World

What is the input canvas?
array / string / tree / graph / grid / table / list / number line

Candidate

What brute-force object is being tried?
subarray / pair / path / subset / row match / interval / state

Multiplicity

How many such candidates are there?
N^2 / 2^N / N! / repeated V+E / repeated MN

Waste

What repeats?
rescan / overlap / rebuild / re-traverse / re-check / duplicate state

Caption

“For every ___, try every ___, then ___.”

That is enough to draw BF for almost any question.

⸻

9. The deepest one-line distinction between BF and Opt drawing

Brute-force drawing

Shows the search space and the waste

Optimized drawing

Shows the state and the invariant

That is the whole difference.

⸻

10. Final compression

If you want one master sentence for the entire How to Draw BF column, it is this:

Draw the input world, then draw the naive search repeating too many times, and make the repeated work impossible to ignore.

That is how to draw brute force across the whole corpus.

