HOW TO DRAW BF COMPLEXITY,GUIDE IN DEPTH COVERING ALL QUESTIONS



Yes — this is a different guide from How to Draw BF.

The key distinction

How to Draw BF

shows:
	•	what the brute-force algorithm does

How to Draw BF Complexity

shows:
	•	why the brute-force algorithm is too expensive

So BF drawing is about mechanics.
BF complexity drawing is about growth.

That means a BF complexity picture should not mainly show the algorithm step-by-step.
It should show:
	•	what repeats,
	•	how often it repeats,
	•	what shape that repetition forms,
	•	and why that shape explodes.

So the right mental model is:

BF complexity drawing = repetition geometry + count formula + waste source

That is the deep rule.

⸻

1) The master purpose of BF complexity drawings

Across the whole corpus, the brute-force complexity visuals are trying to make one of these things obvious:
	•	repeated scans
	•	repeated comparisons
	•	repeated branching
	•	repeated traversal from scratch
	•	repeated rebuild/copy/sort
	•	repeated simulation steps
	•	repeated SQL/table scans
	•	repeated grid/path exploration
	•	repeated arithmetic candidate checking

So when you draw brute-force complexity, you are always answering:

A. What is the repeated unit?

A subarray? A pair? A path? A row scan? A subset? A sort?

B. How many times does it happen?

N, N^2, N^3, 2^N, N!, V(V+E), MN, etc.

C. Why doesn’t it collapse or reuse work?

Because it:
	•	restarts,
	•	recomputes,
	•	overlaps,
	•	branches,
	•	or rebuilds.

That is the full job of the BF complexity visual.

⸻

2) The universal BF complexity formula

For any problem, the best BF complexity drawing follows this template:

Step 1 — Draw one unit of work

Examples:
	•	one subarray scan
	•	one pair comparison
	•	one recursive branch
	•	one path search
	•	one row-to-row join scan
	•	one full sort
	•	one step of simulation

Step 2 — Duplicate the unit

Show it repeated:
	•	for every start index
	•	for every pair
	•	from every node
	•	at every recursion branch
	•	for every row
	•	for every operation

Step 3 — Arrange the repeats in a shape

Use the right geometry:
	•	line
	•	triangle
	•	matrix
	•	cube
	•	tree
	•	forest
	•	wave
	•	funnel
	•	layered timeline

Step 4 — Label the count

Write the actual growth:
	•	N
	•	N^2
	•	N^3
	•	2^N
	•	N!
	•	V + E
	•	V(V+E)
	•	MN
	•	MN * 4^L
	•	etc.

Step 5 — Circle the waste

Mark:
	•	overlap
	•	rescan
	•	restart
	•	duplicate path
	•	repeated sort
	•	repeated scan of same rows
	•	repeated structure conversion

So the visual formula is:

unit of work + repetition geometry + count + waste marker

⸻

3) The deepest rule

BF complexity drawings are not abstract math diagrams

They must remain tied to the problem’s original world.

That means:
	•	arrays should still feel like strips
	•	strings should still feel like text windows/scanners
	•	trees should still feel like recursive branches
	•	graphs should still feel like traversal waves
	•	grids should still feel spatial
	•	SQL should still feel like row joins or repeated scans
	•	design questions should still feel like process replay

You are not drawing “Big-O” in a vacuum.

You are drawing:

Big-O as a consequence of the brute-force behavior in that world

That is the right standard.

⸻

4) The full BF complexity bucket system

I normalized the BF Complexity Vis. column into these major families.

These are the main “complexity picture archetypes” across the corpus.

⸻

Bucket 1 — Exponential / decision-tree explosion

What it means

The brute force branches into choices at each step.

Typical shapes:
	•	binary choice tree
	•	ternary branching tree
	•	k-ary branching tree
	•	subset tree
	•	partition tree
	•	decision tree
	•	state-space explosion tree

What complexity it usually represents
	•	2^N
	•	3^N
	•	K^N
	•	exponential state-space search

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one root
	•	repeated split at each level
	•	leaves exploding outward
	•	optionally highlight repeated states or dead ends

What to emphasize
	•	width explosion
	•	height N
	•	branch count per node
	•	impossible number of leaves

Caption style
	•	“At each index, branch into take/skip”
	•	“Every split creates more splits”
	•	“Choices multiply, not add”

Best visual metaphors
	•	exploding binary tree
	•	branching forest
	•	state-space search tree

Use for
	•	subset brute force
	•	partition brute force
	•	recursive try-all-choices
	•	unpruned recursion

What the drawing should prove

The number of leaves grows exponentially because each step multiplies possibilities.

⸻

Bucket 2 — Factorial / permutation explosion

What it means

The brute force tries every ordering.

This is worse than simple binary branching.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	N!
	•	permutation explosion
	•	arrangement explosion

What to draw

Draw:
	•	a branching tree with shrinking unused pool
	•	or a layered factorial fan
	•	each level picks one remaining item

What to emphasize
	•	first level has N branches
	•	next has N-1
	•	then N-2
	•	then N-3
	•	product becomes factorial

Caption style
	•	“Choose 1st element, then 2nd, then 3rd…”
	•	“Order matters, so every arrangement is generated”

Best metaphors
	•	factorial mountain
	•	permutation tree
	•	arrangement fan

Use for
	•	permutations
	•	ordering/brute arrangement
	•	sequence generation brute force

What the drawing should prove

This is not just many combinations — it is every ordering, so the growth is factorial.

⸻

Bucket 3 — Nested loops / pairwise-comparison web

What it means

The brute force compares many things against many other things.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	O(N^2)
	•	sometimes O(N^2 * check)
	•	sometimes “triangle” instead of full square

What to draw

Use one of these:

A. Full matrix
Rows = outer loop
Columns = inner loop
Every cell = one comparison

B. Upper triangle
If only i < j, draw a triangular matrix

C. Pairwise arc web
Draw elements in a row with many crossing pair lines

What to emphasize
	•	every element compares to many others
	•	often symmetry or redundant overlap
	•	dense crossing or dense matrix fill

Caption style
	•	“For each i, scan all j”
	•	“Every pair is checked”
	•	“Every interval is compared to every interval”

Best metaphors
	•	comparison grid
	•	triangular matrix
	•	dense web of pair lines

Use for
	•	Two Sum brute force
	•	all-pairs comparisons
	•	naive overlap checks
	•	all interval comparisons
	•	many nearest/farthest pair problems

What the drawing should prove

The algorithm spends most of its time pairing things against everything else.

⸻

Bucket 4 — Nested scan triangle / subarray pyramid

What it means

The brute force tries every contiguous range, often with an inner validation scan.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	O(N^2) to enumerate subarrays/substrings
	•	O(N^3) if each candidate is rescanned

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one strip at the top
	•	all possible intervals below it as a triangle or staircase
	•	optionally add mini rescans inside each interval

What to emphasize
	•	many overlapping ranges
	•	same interior cells checked repeatedly
	•	start-end enumeration grows quadratically
	•	full recheck pushes it to cubic

Caption style
	•	“For every start, try every end”
	•	“Then rescan the whole window”
	•	“Overlapping segments are revalidated repeatedly”

Best metaphors
	•	expanding triangle
	•	stepped triangle
	•	pyramid of windows

Use for
	•	substring brute force
	•	subarray brute force
	•	longest valid substring naive check
	•	cubic distinct-count checks

What the drawing should prove

There are quadratically many ranges, and naive validation can make each one expensive.

⸻

Bucket 5 — Grid / matrix / board exhaustive scan

What it means

The brute force repeatedly scans or explores 2D space.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	O(MN)
	•	O(MN * repeated work)
	•	O(MN * paths)
	•	O(N^3) / O(N^4) in some board/combinational settings

What to draw

Draw:
	•	a board or matrix
	•	repeated scan lines
	•	repeated starting points
	•	layered repeated checks
	•	all cells or all rectangles being tested

What to emphasize
	•	spatial redundancy
	•	repeated visits to same cells
	•	repeated row-column scans
	•	dimensional blow-up

Best metaphors
	•	scanning grid
	•	3D cube of combinations
	•	board of repeated checks
	•	rectangle-over-rectangle canvas

Use for
	•	brute-force rectangle/area checks
	•	repeated board validation
	•	naive 2D submatrix work
	•	cell-by-cell repeated search

What the drawing should prove

The cost comes from rewalking or recomputing across 2D space.

⸻

Bucket 6 — Path / graph / tree traversal blow-up

What it means

The brute force explores paths, traversals, or searches from scratch too many times.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	repeated O(V+E) traversals
	•	exponential path search
	•	repeated subtree scans
	•	repeated root-to-leaf or source-to-target runs

What to draw

Draw:
	•	graph/tree once
	•	overlay multiple traversal waves
	•	show same regions revisited
	•	or draw many root-to-leaf path traces

What to emphasize
	•	same edges visited again
	•	same subtree recomputed
	•	repeated source restarts
	•	huge path families

Caption style
	•	“Run a full traversal from every node”
	•	“Explore every path independently”
	•	“Same subtree/path is recalculated many times”

Best metaphors
	•	traversal waves
	•	overlapping paths
	•	repeated graph flood
	•	subtree scan forest

Use for
	•	repeated BFS/DFS from many starts
	•	path enumeration
	•	naive subtree recomputation
	•	graph connectivity checks from scratch

What the drawing should prove

The graph/tree itself is not the problem — the repeated fresh traversals are.

⸻

Bucket 7 — Row-by-row / join / table rescan

What it means

This is the SQL / dataframe brute-force picture.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	nested table scans
	•	correlated subqueries
	•	row-by-row matching
	•	repeated group-by rescans

What to draw

Draw tables:
	•	rows on left
	•	rows on right
	•	arrows showing every row triggering another scan
	•	giant joined result being scanned again

What to emphasize
	•	repeated table passes
	•	row-to-table nested work
	•	correlated query style blow-up
	•	huge intermediate row sets

Caption style
	•	“For each row, scan the whole table again”
	•	“Each join result triggers another aggregation scan”
	•	“Manual row-by-row matching”

Best metaphors
	•	nested loop join
	•	correlated subquery tree
	•	table cross-web
	•	repeated department-wide scan

Use for
	•	SQL brute force
	•	manual joins
	•	repeated grouping/ranking checks

What the drawing should prove

The cost comes from nested row scans, not from a single table pass.

⸻

Bucket 8 — Repeated simulation / process replay

What it means

The brute force simulates the process literally, step by step, too many times.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	repeated time-step simulation
	•	repeated station/process cycles
	•	repeated full replay after each operation
	•	per-step whole-state updates

What to draw

Draw:
	•	timeline
	•	stations or process boxes
	•	the same state being replayed over and over
	•	arrows cycling repeatedly

What to emphasize
	•	every step is simulated literally
	•	no skipping or summarizing
	•	same process repeated from many starts
	•	state replay instead of abstraction

Caption style
	•	“Simulate every minute/turn/step”
	•	“Replay the full cycle from each starting point”
	•	“Process evolves one slow step at a time”

Best metaphors
	•	clock/timeline
	•	blender/cycle
	•	station loop
	•	conveyor replay

Use for
	•	gas-station naive simulation
	•	process scheduling naive simulation
	•	literal state evolution questions
	•	repeated cyclic checks

What the drawing should prove

The brute force is slow because it simulates the world in tiny steps instead of jumping by structure.

⸻

Bucket 9 — Sort / rebuild / delete / copy overhead

What it means

The brute force keeps rebuilding, copying, sorting, or converting structures.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	repeated sorting
	•	repeated deletion/rescanning
	•	repeated conversion overhead
	•	expensive copying

What to draw

Draw:
	•	an input pile
	•	a funnel into sort/copy/convert box
	•	a new rebuilt structure each time
	•	repeated rebuild arrows

What to emphasize
	•	repeated full reconstruction
	•	extra O(N log N) sorts
	•	repeated copies
	•	repeated structural rebuild

Caption style
	•	“Rebuild the whole structure each time”
	•	“Sort after each change”
	•	“Convert to another representation, then back”

Best metaphors
	•	sorting funnel
	•	copy machine
	•	rebuild pipeline
	•	delete-and-repack machine

Use for
	•	repeated resorting
	•	list→array→list conversions
	•	repeated slicing/copying
	•	deletion-heavy brute force

What the drawing should prove

The waste is not only search — it is all the extra rebuilding.

⸻

Bucket 10 — Substring / character / window rescans

What it means

The brute force repeatedly rechecks text windows or character properties from scratch.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	O(N^2) substring enumeration
	•	O(N^3) if each substring is rescanned/validated
	•	repeated frequency scans

What to draw

Draw:
	•	string strip
	•	many windows
	•	scanner bars moving inside each one
	•	character counts recalculated repeatedly

What to emphasize
	•	text windows overlap heavily
	•	frequency/stat checks restart every time
	•	same characters are revisited in many windows

Caption style
	•	“Extract every substring, then scan it”
	•	“Recompute character counts for each window”
	•	“Filter windows one by one”

Best metaphors
	•	scanner
	•	conveyor belt filters
	•	substring microscope
	•	repeated character pipeline

Use for
	•	string brute-force questions
	•	anagram/unique-char naive checks
	•	text-filtering and repeated search

What the drawing should prove

The complexity comes from re-reading the same characters across overlapping windows.

⸻

Bucket 11 — Repeated linear scan / pipeline

What it means

The brute force is “only linear” per operation, but the problem makes that linear pass happen too many times.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	O(N^2) from repeated O(N) scans
	•	O(QN) for Q repeated queries/operations
	•	“scan whole list per operation”

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one pipeline/scan bar
	•	then many repeated copies of that bar
	•	often stacked vertically to show repetition

What to emphasize
	•	a linear scan is cheap once, expensive many times
	•	repeated whole-list pass
	•	one slow search bar per operation/query

Caption style
	•	“Do one full scan for every query”
	•	“Search the whole list every time”
	•	“Each operation triggers another linear pass”

Best metaphors
	•	search bar moving across list
	•	pipeline funnel
	•	repeated scan tape
	•	vertical stack of linear passes

Use for
	•	repeated stack/list scans
	•	repeated search per pop/query
	•	repeated pass over active structure

What the drawing should prove

Linear is not the problem — repeated linear is.

⸻

Bucket 12 — Numeric candidate sweep / arithmetic brute force

What it means

The brute force walks through many candidate values or recomputes arithmetic facts directly.

What complexity it usually represents
	•	trial division
	•	candidate-by-candidate checks
	•	full numeric sweep
	•	repeated digit/bit recomputation

What to draw

Draw:
	•	number line
	•	candidate points
	•	repeated tests above each point
	•	digit/bit columns being recomputed

What to emphasize
	•	too many candidate values
	•	arithmetic repeated without reuse
	•	one-by-one search through numeric space

Caption style
	•	“Try every candidate value”
	•	“Check every divisor / number / digit arrangement”
	•	“Recompute numeric property from scratch”

Best metaphors
	•	infinite number line
	•	trial-division ruler
	•	digit weight columns
	•	arithmetic test harness

Use for
	•	divisor trial brute force
	•	candidate search over large number range
	•	repeated digit/bit checks

What the drawing should prove

The complexity comes from testing candidate values directly instead of exploiting structure.

⸻

Bucket 13 — Specialized exact brute-force metaphor

Your corpus has a long tail of custom exact BF complexity phrases:
	•	“Two Funnels into One”
	•	“Tangled Flowchart”
	•	“Exploding Array”
	•	“The Eraser”
	•	“The Shell Game”
	•	“The Data Shuffler”
	•	and many other one-off metaphors

These are still valid BF complexity drawings.

Rule for handling them

Map them to one of these three deeper questions:
	1.	Is it a repeat problem?
	2.	Is it a branching problem?
	3.	Is it a rebuild/copy/simulation problem?

That lets you keep the metaphor while still grounding the complexity.

⸻

5) How to choose the right BF complexity shape

This is the most important practical part.

If the brute force repeats over all pairs

Draw:
	•	matrix
	•	upper triangle
	•	arc web

If it repeats over all ranges

Draw:
	•	triangle
	•	staircase
	•	window pyramid

If it branches recursively

Draw:
	•	tree
	•	forest
	•	decision DAG/tree

If it tries all orderings

Draw:
	•	factorial tree with shrinking choices

If it repeatedly scans a board

Draw:
	•	grid with many scan lines / repeated rectangles / repeated start points

If it repeatedly traverses graph/tree paths

Draw:
	•	overlapping traversal waves or path forest

If it repeatedly simulates time/process

Draw:
	•	timeline / cyclic station loop / process replay diagram

If it repeatedly rebuilds or sorts

Draw:
	•	funnel / copy pipeline / rebuild machine

If it repeatedly scans rows/tables

Draw:
	•	nested row-to-table arrows / join web

If it repeatedly sweeps candidate values

Draw:
	•	number line / candidate ticks / repeated arithmetic checks

That is the practical decision tree.

⸻

6) The difference between BF algorithm drawing and BF complexity drawing

This is the most common confusion.

BF algorithm drawing

Shows:
	•	what is being tried

Example:
	•	all substrings as brackets

BF complexity drawing

Shows:
	•	why trying them is expensive

Example:
	•	a triangular pyramid of all substrings, plus rescans inside each one, plus O(N^3)

So:
	•	algorithm drawing focuses on behavior
	•	complexity drawing focuses on growth

The complexity picture is always more abstract and more repetitive.

⸻

7) The in-depth BF complexity checklist

For any question, draw BF complexity like this:

1. Name the brute-force unit

What is one operation family?
	•	one pair comparison
	•	one substring validation
	•	one branch
	•	one path
	•	one row rescan
	•	one sort
	•	one simulation step

2. Ask how many units exist
	•	N
	•	N^2
	•	2^N
	•	N!
	•	QN
	•	V(V+E)
	•	etc.

3. Ask if each unit has inner work

This is where many O(N^2) become O(N^3).

Examples:
	•	enumerate all windows = O(N^2)
	•	then scan each window = O(N^3)

4. Ask whether work overlaps

Do the same states/paths/ranges get recomputed?

5. Choose a geometry
	•	line
	•	triangle
	•	matrix
	•	cube
	•	tree
	•	forest
	•	wave
	•	funnel
	•	timeline

6. Add one sentence

“For every ___, do ___, then ___ again.”

7. Add the final asymptotic label

Put it visually beside the shape.

That is the full BF complexity workflow.

⸻

8) What makes a bad BF complexity drawing

Avoid these mistakes:

Mistake 1 — Drawing only one attempt

That explains the algorithm, not the complexity.

Mistake 2 — Writing Big-O without a shape

That gives the answer but not the intuition.

Mistake 3 — Losing the original world

If the problem is a grid, the complexity should still feel spatial.

Mistake 4 — Not showing the inner repeated cost

A lot of brute-force mistakes come from hidden inner checks.

Mistake 5 — Making the BF drawing too clean

The whole point is that brute force should visually feel inefficient.

⸻

9) The deepest compression

If I compress the whole BF Complexity Vis. column into one law, it is this:

Draw brute-force complexity as the geometry of repeated work.

That repeated work usually appears as:
	•	a triangle of ranges,
	•	a matrix of pair checks,
	•	a tree of recursive choices,
	•	a forest of path explorations,
	•	a grid/cube of spatial checks,
	•	a timeline of step-by-step replay,
	•	a funnel of rebuild/sort/copy,
	•	or a row-web of nested table scans.

That is the full mental model.

⸻

10) The single best one-line rule

When drawing brute-force complexity, do this:

show one unit of work, then visually multiply it until the asymptotic growth becomes obvious.

That is how to draw BF complexity across the whole corpus.

