HOW TO DRAW OPT,GUIDE IN DEPTH COVERING ALL QUESTIONS



Yes — here is the in-depth “How to Draw (Opt)” guide for the full corpus.

This is the most important drawing layer, because the optimized drawing is where the problem stops being “a lot of work” and becomes “a controlled machine.”

The key distinction is:
	•	How to Draw BF shows the naive search.
	•	BF Complexity Vis. shows why it blows up.
	•	How to Draw (Opt) shows the compressed state that avoids the blow-up.

So the deepest rule is:

Optimized drawing = state + motion + invariant + helper structure + answer update

That is the heart of almost every optimized diagram in your source.

⸻

1) What “How to Draw (Opt)” is really doing

Across the whole corpus, the optimized drawing is trying to make five things visible:

A. The right canvas

What world the algorithm lives in:
	•	strip
	•	table
	•	grid
	•	node-link
	•	graph
	•	chart
	•	container
	•	formula board
	•	state table
	•	bit/range blocks
	•	process box

B. The active state

What minimum information matters now:
	•	L, R
	•	current node
	•	queue frontier
	•	stack contents
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	current prefix sum
	•	current best answer
	•	heap top
	•	visited set
	•	carry / parity / mask

C. The motion rule

What changes each step:
	•	pointer moves
	•	window expands/shrinks
	•	node gets linked
	•	frontier spreads
	•	state cell fills
	•	bit flips
	•	interval merges
	•	count updates
	•	rank/group forms
	•	object state mutates

D. The invariant

What remains true after every update:
	•	window stays valid
	•	stack remains monotonic
	•	heap top is best active candidate
	•	dp dependencies are already solved
	•	subtree result is correct when returned
	•	visited prevents repeats
	•	prefix structure summarizes all previous information

E. The answer extraction

Where the result comes from:
	•	best window length
	•	table cell
	•	root/subtree return
	•	last processed node
	•	heap top
	•	aggregate count
	•	constructed output path/list/object

So optimized drawing is not just “show the algorithm.”
It is:

show the smallest live state that is sufficient to prove correctness

That is the deep standard.

⸻

2) The universal optimized drawing formula

For almost any question, you can draw the optimized solution with this template:

Step 1

Pick the correct world canvas.

Step 2

Draw only the active state, not the entire search space.

Step 3

Show the single legal motion the algorithm performs.

Step 4

Write the invariant beside the drawing.

Step 5

Show where the answer is updated or read.

So the universal formula is:

Canvas + active state + legal motion + invariant + answer box

That is the full optimized drawing grammar.

⸻

3) The deepest contrast: BF vs Opt

Brute Force drawing

shows:
	•	the candidate space
	•	repetition
	•	overlap
	•	blow-up

Optimized drawing

shows:
	•	the compressed live state
	•	the efficient motion rule
	•	the invariant that prevents rework

So the optimized picture should feel:
	•	smaller
	•	cleaner
	•	more structured
	•	more stable
	•	more intentional

It should look like a machine, not a crowd.

⸻

4) The 12 optimized drawing buckets

These cover essentially the full corpus.

⸻

Bucket 1 — Strip / Timeline / Pointer Canvas

This is the core optimized bucket for arrays and strings.

When to use

Use this when the optimized solution works by:
	•	one pass
	•	two pointers
	•	sliding window
	•	center expansion
	•	partition search
	•	boundary movement
	•	prefix/suffix sweep

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one horizontal strip
	•	indices below
	•	1–3 moving markers above
	•	optionally a shaded active region

Active state

Usually:
	•	L, R
	•	i, j
	•	mid
	•	current best range
	•	partition boundary
	•	running total / count box nearby

Motion

Show only the valid motion:
	•	R++
	•	L++
	•	inward pinch
	•	center expansion
	•	sweep left→right
	•	split at mid
	•	merge from left/right streams

Invariants

Examples:
	•	“window contains no duplicates”
	•	“everything before i is processed”
	•	“left side < target, right side > target”
	•	“partition condition checked at mid”
	•	“current range is valid”

Best mini-templates

Sliding Window

Draw:
	•	substring strip
	•	[L ... R]
	•	side frequency box
	•	answer box: best length/window

Caption:
expand R, shrink L until invariant is restored

Two Pointers

Draw:
	•	sorted array strip
	•	L and R arrows
	•	sum/condition in center
	•	answer marker if found

Caption:
move the side that can improve the condition

Prefix/Suffix pass

Draw:
	•	strip
	•	one forward sweep arrow
	•	one backward sweep arrow
	•	small arrays/boxes for prefix/suffix summaries

Caption:
carry cumulative information forward/backward once

What the drawing should prove

The algorithm never restarts; it moves through the sequence with controlled boundaries and maintained state.

