5) The universal style guide for optimized drawings

Rule 1 — Draw less than brute force

The optimized picture should feel compressed.

Rule 2 — Draw only the live state

Do not draw the whole search space.
Draw only what the algorithm currently maintains.

Rule 3 — Show one legal motion

One push, one pop, one pointer move, one state transition, one merge, one relaxation.

Rule 4 — Write the invariant explicitly

This is the single most important text label.

Examples:
	•	“window valid”
	•	“top = smallest active”
	•	“state solved once”
	•	“parent summarizes children”
	•	“visited prevents repeats”

Rule 5 — Show the answer location

Always indicate where the answer comes from:
	•	best-length box
	•	dp final cell
	•	heap top
	•	output list
	•	root return
	•	component count
	•	final aggregate

Rule 6 — Make helper structures visible

If the optimization comes from memory or ordering, draw it.
Examples:
	•	map
	•	queue
	•	heap
	•	stack
	•	memo table
	•	prefix array
	•	visited board
	•	linked list + hashmap combo

Rule 7 — Preserve the problem’s natural world

Do not turn a tree problem into an array unless the intended optimized state really is array-based.

⸻

6) The optimized drawing checklist

For any problem, fill this in:

1. Canvas

What world am I drawing on?
strip / grid / node-link / graph / table / state-table / formula / container / process

2. Active state

What minimum objects matter now?
L, R / current node / queue / dp cell / heap top / mask / carry / group

3. Motion

What changes in one valid step?
move / push / pop / attach / fill / relax / merge / flip / consume

4. Invariant

What must remain true?
________________________________

5. Answer box

Where is the result read or updated?
best length / dp[n] / final node / aggregate / top of heap

That is enough to draw optimized logic for almost any question.

⸻

7) The most common mistake in optimized drawings

The biggest failure is this:

Mistake

Drawing the optimized algorithm as just a cleaner brute force.

That is wrong.

The optimized drawing should not show “fewer candidates.”
It should show:
	•	the compressed state,
	•	the update rule,
	•	and the invariant that makes extra candidates unnecessary.

If you still feel like you are drawing the candidate space, you are not at the optimized layer yet.

⸻

8) How to know your optimized drawing is correct

A good optimized drawing answers these five questions visually:
	1.	What is the live state?
	2.	What changes in one step?
	3.	Why is that step legal?
	4.	What information is being reused instead of recomputed?
	5.	Where does the answer come from?

If the drawing cannot answer those, it is still too vague.

⸻

9) The deepest one-line rule

Optimized drawing should make the invariant visible.

That is the best compression of the entire How to Draw (Opt) column.

Because the optimized solution is not really “faster code.”
It is:

a smaller state that is updated under a stronger rule

That is what the diagram must show.

⸻

10) Final compression

If I compress the whole optimized-drawing system into one sentence:

Draw the smallest live machine that preserves the right invariant and updates the answer without redoing old work.

That is how to draw the optimized solution across the whole corpus.

The natural next companion would be:

“How to Draw Opt Complexity” — the proof pictures for why each optimized drawing actually achieves its time bound.




HOW TO DRAW OPT COMPLEXITY,GUIDE IN DEPTH COVERING ALL QUESTIONS





Yes — this is the in-depth “How to Draw Opt Complexity” guide for the full corpus.

This is a different layer from:
	•	How to Draw BF → what naive search does
	•	BF Complexity Vis. → why naive search explodes
	•	How to Draw (Opt) → what the optimized live state looks like

Now we are at:

How to Draw Opt Complexity = how to visually prove the optimized time bound

That is the key.

The optimized complexity drawing is not mainly about the algorithm’s state.
It is about the proof shape of the runtime.

So the deepest rule is:

Opt complexity drawing = bounded movement + bounded touches + bounded structure cost

That is what almost every row in your source is trying to show.

⸻

1) What “Opt Complexity Vis.” is really doing

After scanning the full corpus, the optimized-complexity layer repeatedly tries to show one of these ideas:
	•	one pass
	•	two passes
	•	one visit per node
	•	one touch per cell
	•	each pointer moves at most N
	•	sort once, then sweep
	•	logarithmic halving
	•	heap/ordered structure gives log factor
	•	states × transitions
	•	amortized push/pop once
	•	preprocess once, answer fast
	•	range hierarchy shrinks the work
	•	one operation touches only a constant number of internal pieces

So optimized complexity pictures are not random.
They are visual proofs of one of a small number of runtime laws.

⸻

2) The big distinction: optimized drawing vs optimized complexity drawing

How to Draw (Opt)

shows:
	•	the live state
	•	the motion rule
	•	the invariant
	•	the answer update

Opt Complexity drawing

shows:
	•	why the live state moves only a limited number of times
	•	why each unit is processed a bounded number of times
	•	where the log factor comes from if it exists
	•	where preprocessing cost ends and query cost begins
	•	why amortization makes the total smaller than it looks

So:

optimized drawing = mechanics

optimized complexity drawing = cost proof

That is the most important difference.

⸻

3) The universal Opt Complexity formula

For almost any optimized solution, the complexity drawing should answer these five questions:

1. What is the unit being processed?
	•	element
	•	node
	•	edge
	•	cell
	•	state
	•	query
	•	update
	•	candidate answer
	•	heap entry
	•	stack item
	•	interval block

2. How many units are there?
	•	N
	•	M x N
	•	V + E
	•	number of DP states
	•	number of queries
	•	answer-range halving count
	•	number of events

3. How many times can each unit be touched?
	•	once
	•	twice
	•	pushed once / popped once
	•	log N levels
	•	constant transition count
	•	one successful settle/visit

4. Is there any preprocessing?
	•	sort once
	•	build once
	•	precompute once
	•	fill table once

5. What is the final total?

Examples:
	•	O(N)
	•	O(N log N)
	•	O(MN)
	•	O(V+E)
	•	O(states × transitions)
	•	O(check_cost × log range)

So the universal proof formula is:

unit × touches-per-unit + preprocessing + structure overhead

That is the deep runtime mental model.

⸻

4) The core optimized-complexity buckets

These buckets cover essentially the entire corpus.

⸻

Bucket 1 — Single linear sweep

This is the most common optimized-complexity picture in the whole corpus.

What it means

The algorithm processes the input in one directional pass.

Typical complexities
	•	O(N)
	•	O(M+N)
	•	O(max(M,N))

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one straight horizontal line
	•	or one arrow from left to right
	•	or one timeline from 0 to N

What to emphasize
	•	no restarting
	•	no nested rescans
	•	every element seen once
	•	all work is attached to this one sweep

Caption styles
	•	“single pass”
	•	“linear scan”
	•	“one sweep”
	•	“one traversal”

Best visual metaphors
	•	straight arrow
	•	conveyor belt
	•	timeline
	•	one sweep line

Use for
	•	direct scans
	•	prefix/suffix passes
	•	counting
	•	simple greedy
	•	one-pass hash-map problems
	•	single array/string traversals

What the drawing should prove

Every element contributes to the runtime only once in a single forward sweep.

⸻

Bucket 2 — Bounded two-pointer / amortized boundary movement

This is still often O(N), but needs a different proof than a plain one-pass scan.

What it means

Two or more pointers move, but the total movement is still bounded.

Typical complexities
	•	O(N)
	•	amortized O(N)

What to draw

Draw:
	•	array/string strip
	•	left and right arrows
	•	each arrow moving only forward (or inward)
	•	no backward resets

What to emphasize
	•	L moves at most N times
	•	R moves at most N times
	•	total pointer moves = O(N), not O(N^2)

Caption styles
	•	“each pointer only advances”
	•	“two monotone pointers”
	•	“expand and shrink, but never restart”

Best metaphors
	•	inchworm
	•	zipper
	•	dual sweep
	•	converging arrows

Use for
	•	sliding window
	•	two pointers
	•	merge streams
	•	some greedy boundary logic
	•	deques/windows

What the drawing should prove

Although there are two loops conceptually, pointer movement is monotone, so total work is linear.

⸻

Bucket 3 — Constant-time side operation on top of a sweep

This is extremely common for optimized hash-based solutions.

What it means

The main cost is linear traversal, and each step does an O(1) helper operation.

Typical complexities
	•	O(N)
	•	O(M+N) with constant-time lookups
	•	O(1) auxiliary operation per element

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one main horizontal arrow
	•	tiny boxes off each step representing:
	•	hash lookup
	•	count update
	•	set check
	•	constant math update

What to emphasize
	•	helper work does not create nested growth
	•	lookup/update is constant-ish per step
	•	total remains linear

Caption styles
	•	“single scan + O(1) lookup”
	•	“one pass with constant-time updates”
	•	“flat line plus tiny side box”

Best metaphors
	•	main pipeline + tiny side taps
	•	line + constant branch node
	•	arrow + micro-lookup block

Use for
	•	Two Sum optimized
	•	group/frequency/hash problems
	•	prefix-state hash map
	•	dictionary/set lookups during scan

What the drawing should prove

The extra helper structure does not multiply runtime; it only adds constant work per processed item.

⸻

Bucket 4 — Sort once, then linear work

This is one of the most important hybrid complexity pictures.

What it means

The expensive step is sorting.
Everything afterward is linear or near-linear.

Typical complexities
	•	O(N log N)
	•	sometimes O(N log N + N) simplified to O(N log N)

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one large sort box labeled O(N log N)
	•	then a single sweep line or one-pass arrow after it

What to emphasize
	•	sorting dominates
	•	post-sort processing is cheap
	•	total is governed by the sorting bottleneck

Caption styles
	•	“sort, then sweep”
	•	“sorting bottleneck”
	•	“order once, process once”

Best metaphors
	•	funnel into sorter
	•	sorter block + conveyor
	•	big box followed by one thin arrow

Use for
	•	interval merge
	•	greedy after sort
	•	two-pointers on sorted input
	•	rank/order problems
	•	event-based sweep

What the drawing should prove

Global order is paid for once; afterward the algorithm only walks the ordered result cheaply.

⸻

Bucket 5 — Logarithmic halving

This is the clean binary-search proof shape.

What it means

Each step cuts the search space substantially, usually in half.

Typical complexities
	•	O(log N)
	•	O(log range)

What to draw

Draw:
	•	shrinking blocks
	•	a bar halved repeatedly
	•	stair steps of size N, N/2, N/4, N/8...

What to emphasize
	•	search space shrinks geometrically
	•	number of halvings is logarithmic
	•	only one branch continues each round

Caption styles
	•	“halve the range”
	•	“block shrinks geometrically”
	•	“binary partition”

Best metaphors
	•	chopped log
	•	shrinking rectangle
	•	halving staircase
	•	Russian-doll blocks

Use for
	•	classic binary search
	•	boundary search
	•	binary lifting style jumps (conceptually)
	•	logarithmic search over ordered structures

What the drawing should prove

Progress is multiplicative, not additive, so the number of steps is logarithmic.

⸻

Bucket 6 — Answer-space binary search + checker

This is a specialized complexity picture that needs two layers.

What it means

Binary search is over candidate answers, and each guess runs a checker.

Typical complexities
	•	O(check_cost × log answer_range)
	•	for example O(N log M)

What to draw

Draw:
	•	halving blocks for the answer range on top
	•	under each candidate, one linear checker bar

What to emphasize
	•	outer log number of guesses
	•	inner linear/greedy/prefix/window check
	•	multiplication of two costs

Caption styles
	•	“log guesses, linear feasibility check”
	•	“search the answer, not the array”
	•	“outer binary search, inner validator”

Best metaphors
	•	stacked halving blocks with scan bar inside each layer
	•	decision ladder + check pipeline

Use for
	•	Koko Eating Bananas
	•	ship packages within D days
	•	minimize maximum / maximize minimum
	•	threshold feasibility problems

What the drawing should prove

The expensive part is not the search alone, but the repeated checker multiplied by logarithmic guesses.

⸻

Bucket 7 — One visit per node / edge / cell

This is the graph/tree/grid traversal proof bucket.

What it means

The optimized traversal touches each structural unit a bounded number of times.

Typical complexities
	•	O(N) for tree traversal
	•	O(V+E) for graph traversal
	•	O(MN) for grid traversal

What to draw

Choose by world:
	•	tree: one trace through each node
	•	graph: frontier wave touching each node/edge
	•	grid: each cell marked once

What to emphasize
	•	visited prevents repeats
	•	edges are processed bounded times
	•	cells/nodes become “done” once settled

Caption styles
	•	“visit each node once”
	•	“each edge is relaxed/processed once or a bounded number of times”
	•	“paint each cell once”

Best metaphors
	•	one weaving path through structure
	•	frontier wave
	•	filled cells
	•	node check marks

Use for
	•	DFS/BFS
	•	tree recursion
	•	topological traversal
	•	component counting
	•	flood fill

What the drawing should prove

Traversal is linear in structure size because no region is re-explored indefinitely.

⸻

Bucket 8 — State-table fill: states × transitions

This is the canonical DP complexity picture.

What it means

Runtime is determined by:
	•	how many states exist
	•	how many transitions are evaluated per state

Typical complexities
	•	O(N)
	•	O(MN)
	•	O(N^2)
	•	O(states × transitions)
	•	sometimes O(2^N × N) for bitmask DP

What to draw

Draw:
	•	the DP table/grid/row
	•	arrows into each cell
	•	optionally annotate “constant transitions” or “K transitions per cell”

What to emphasize
	•	each state is solved once
	•	recurrence uses bounded predecessor work
	•	fill order avoids recomputation

Caption styles
	•	“fill each state once”
	•	“bounded transitions per state”
	•	“table size drives runtime”

Best metaphors
	•	spreadsheet filling
	•	state lattice
	•	arrow-fed cells

Use for
	•	1D DP
	•	2D DP
	•	edit distance
	•	interval DP
	•	memoized DFS collapsed into state graph
	•	bitmask DP

What the drawing should prove

Time is not about recursion depth anymore; it is about the number of unique states and edges between them.

⸻

Bucket 9 — Amortized push/pop once

This is the proof bucket for monotonic stacks, deques, and similar structures.

What it means

Even though there is popping inside a loop, each element enters and leaves only once.

Typical complexities
	•	amortized O(N)

What to draw

Draw:
	•	stream of elements
	•	stack/deque container
	•	each element tagged with one push and one pop
	•	optionally crossed out after pop

What to emphasize
	•	no element is popped repeatedly
	•	pushes and pops sum to O(N)
	•	inner while loop does not imply quadratic cost

Caption styles
	•	“each item enters once, leaves once”
	•	“pops are paid for by earlier pushes”
	•	“amortized linear”

Best metaphors
	•	ticketed entry/exit
	•	stack with one-time lifecycles
	•	toll-gate accounting

Use for
	•	monotonic stack
	•	monotonic deque
	•	path simplification stacks
	•	lazy-transfer stack/queue tricks

What the drawing should prove

The scary inner loop is harmless because total lifetime operations per element are bounded.

⸻

Bucket 10 — Heap / ordered-structure logarithmic maintenance

This is the proof bucket when the algorithm needs a dynamic best element.

What it means

Each insert/remove/update touches a logarithmic-height ordered structure.

Typical complexities
	•	O(N log N)
	•	O(K log N)
	•	O((V+E) log V) in graph settings
	•	per operation O(log N)

What to draw

Draw:
	•	heap as a tree or funnel
	•	each operation touching only height log N
	•	multiple items entering/exiting

What to emphasize
	•	structure height, not full size
	•	repeated operations each cost log
	•	total = operations × log factor

Caption styles
	•	“log-height maintenance”
	•	“each insertion/extraction touches one root-to-leaf path”
	•	“priority access in logarithmic time”

Best metaphors
	•	tournament tree
	•	funnel to root
	•	shallow branching tree

Use for
	•	top K
	•	Dijkstra
	•	schedule optimization
	•	active interval heap
	•	median maintenance

What the drawing should prove

Dynamic ordering is not free, but it is much cheaper than full resorting every time.

⸻

Bucket 11 — Union-find / almost-constant merge-find structure

This is a more specialized proof picture.

What it means

Connectivity operations are kept cheap through parent compression and union structure.

Typical complexities
	•	near-linear overall
	•	often treated as almost O(1) per operation in practice
	•	formally O(α(N)) amortized per op

What to draw

Draw:
	•	components as trees
	•	parent links compressing upward
	•	merges joining roots
	•	flattened paths after finds

What to emphasize
	•	repeated finds become cheaper
	•	unions only attach roots
	•	total remains near-linear

Caption styles
	•	“compressed parent chains”
	•	“merge components, don’t rescan graph”
	•	“path compression flattens future work”

Best metaphors
	•	shrinking trees
	•	collapsing ladders
	•	component merge map

Use for
	•	account merge
	•	number of components
	•	redundant connection
	•	dynamic island union

What the drawing should prove

Repeated connectivity checks are cheap because the structure remembers component history.

⸻

Bucket 12 — Range hierarchy / logarithmic query decomposition

This is for segment trees, BITs, sparse tables, binary lifting, etc.

What it means

Work is done over summarized blocks or jumps rather than raw ranges.

Typical complexities
	•	O(log N) per query/update
	•	O(log^2 N) in some layered structures
	•	preprocessing O(N log N) + fast queries

What to draw

Draw:
	•	interval blocks stacked hierarchically
	•	binary indexed jumps
	•	powers-of-two ancestor ladders
	•	query decomposed into a few covering blocks

What to emphasize
	•	range is represented by few blocks
	•	updates/queries walk only height or jump layers
	•	hierarchy replaces raw scanning

Caption styles
	•	“cover range with a few summary blocks”
	•	“climb by powers of two”
	•	“log-height tree of summaries”

Best metaphors
	•	block tower
	•	summary tree
	•	jump ladder

Use for
	•	segment tree
	•	Fenwick tree
	•	sparse table
	•	binary lifting
	•	RMQ/LCA structures

What the drawing should prove

The algorithm avoids scanning whole ranges by navigating a logarithmic summary hierarchy.

⸻

Bucket 13 — Preprocess once, answer many

This is a major proof pattern, especially in queries and repeated operations.

What it means

The expensive work is front-loaded.
Queries afterward are cheap.

Typical complexities
	•	build O(N) or O(N log N)
	•	per query O(1) / O(log N)
	•	total depends on query count

What to draw

Draw:
	•	big preprocessing box once
	•	many small query arrows afterward

What to emphasize
	•	one-time build cost
	•	query phase separated
	•	total amortizes well when there are many queries

Caption styles
	•	“pay once, reuse many times”
	•	“build summary structure, then query cheaply”
	•	“front-loaded computation”

Best metaphors
	•	factory setup + production line
	•	map build + fast lookups
	•	preprocessing wall + tiny query taps

Use for
	•	prefix sum
	•	sparse table
	•	preprocessing first/last positions
	•	adjacency/build phases
	•	SQL indexes/conceptual grouped summaries

What the drawing should prove

Expensive one-time preparation is justified because repeated future work becomes tiny.

⸻

Bucket 14 — Constant-state formula / invariant maintenance

This is the complexity proof bucket for math-first optimized solutions.

What it means

The algorithm does tiny scalar work per item or per digit.

Typical complexities
	•	O(N)
	•	O(log N) over digits/bits
	•	O(1) in closed-form cases

What to draw

Draw:
	•	one or a few variable boxes
	•	digits/values entering
	•	accumulator updates
	•	no large side structures

What to emphasize
	•	constant number of variables
	•	bounded work per step
	•	arithmetic/invariant maintenance replaces search

Caption styles
	•	“constant-state update”
	•	“one arithmetic step per digit/item”
	•	“closed-form or direct formula”

Best metaphors
	•	calculator register
	•	carry chain
	•	xor/parity box

Use for
	•	carry/number problems
	•	xor/parity logic
	•	simple number-theory scans
	•	formula-based solutions

What the drawing should prove

The optimized solution is cheap because it stores only a tiny invariant and updates it directly.

⸻

Bucket 15 — Process/object local-touch complexity

This is the design/API/runtime-proof bucket.

What it means

Each operation touches only a few internal components, not the whole system.

Typical complexities
	•	O(1) per operation
	•	O(log N) per operation if ordered structure involved
	•	amortized O(1) with buffered/lazy designs

What to draw

Draw:
	•	object box
	•	internal sub-boxes
	•	one operation path through only the affected pieces

What to emphasize
	•	local mutation only
	•	no full rebuild
	•	persistent state avoids replay
	•	operation cost is independent of total history size or only log-sized

Caption styles
	•	“touch only the hot path”
	•	“update one node, one map entry, one list edge”
	•	“buffer leftovers instead of rereading”

Best metaphors
	•	circuit trace
	•	hot path
	•	localized repair
	•	cache touch path

Use for
	•	LRU/LFU
	•	iterator wrappers
	•	Read4-style buffering
	•	queue/stack API design
	•	async/process state designs

What the drawing should prove

Efficient design comes from maintaining the right internal state so each call only changes a small local region.

⸻

5) The best style guide for Opt Complexity drawings

Rule 1 — Draw the proof, not the code

Do not redraw the whole algorithm.
Draw why the cost is bounded.

Rule 2 — Show the counted unit

Always make it obvious what is being counted:
	•	element
	•	pointer move
	•	node
	•	edge
	•	state
	•	heap op
	•	query
	•	block

Rule 3 — Show bounded lifetime

If amortized, tag each unit with its maximum number of actions.

Examples:
	•	pushed once, popped once
	•	visited once
	•	one settle per node
	•	one fill per state
	•	log-height path per update

Rule 4 — Separate preprocessing from runtime if needed

For many structures the proof is:
	•	build once
	•	query many

Draw those as separate phases.

Rule 5 — Show the dominating term visually

If sort dominates, make the sort box bigger.
If binary search checker dominates, show scan bar inside each log layer.
If heap maintenance dominates, show log-height tree touches.

Rule 6 — Keep it in the problem’s original world

The proof picture should still feel native to the problem:
	•	strips for arrays
	•	nodes for trees
	•	cells for grids
	•	rows for SQL
	•	objects for design

⸻

6) The full Opt Complexity checklist

For any problem, draw optimized complexity like this:

1. What is the processed unit?

element / node / edge / cell / state / query / operation / candidate

2. How many such units exist?

N / MxN / V+E / states / queries / log(range)

3. How many times can each unit be touched?

once / twice / pushed+popped once / log N / constant transitions

4. Is there preprocessing?

sort / build / precompute / compress

5. Is there a structure overhead?

heap log / tree height / block hierarchy / map lookup / DSU compression

6. What dominates the total?

N / N log N / V+E / states x transitions / check x log(range)

That is the full proof workflow.

⸻

7) How to choose the right Opt Complexity shape fast

Use this decision tree.

If it is basically one pass

Draw single linear sweep

If there are two moving boundaries but no resets

Draw bounded two-pointer amortization

If there is a hash/helper operation each step

Draw linear sweep + tiny O(1) side box

If sorting happens first

Draw sort box + linear sweep

If the search space halves

Draw halving blocks

If each guess runs a checker

Draw halving blocks + check bar

If it visits structure once

Draw one-visit-per-node/edge/cell

If it is DP

Draw states × transitions

If a stack/deque has inner while loops

Draw push once / pop once amortized

If a heap maintains best active item

Draw log-height ordered structure

If range structure summarizes blocks

Draw hierarchical range decomposition

If it builds once and answers many

Draw preprocess once, query many

If it is a design object

Draw local-touch hot path

⸻

8) The most common mistakes in Opt Complexity drawings

Mistake 1 — Redrawing the optimized algorithm instead of proving cost

That duplicates “How to Draw (Opt)” instead of “Opt Complexity.”

Mistake 2 — Writing Big-O with no geometry

That states the answer, but not the intuition.

Mistake 3 — Ignoring amortization

Especially bad for:
	•	monotonic stack
	•	deque
	•	lazy transfer
	•	union-find

Mistake 4 — Hiding the preprocessing phase

A lot of algorithms are only fast because they pay an up-front cost once.

Mistake 5 — Not showing the dominating term

For hybrid algorithms, one cost usually dominates:
	•	sorting
	•	log-height structure
	•	answer-space checker
	•	DP table size

Your picture must make that obvious.

⸻

9) The deepest one-line rule

Optimized complexity drawings should show why no work is repeated unnecessarily.

That is the single best compression.

Because every optimized algorithm is really proving one of these:
	•	each unit is touched once
	•	each boundary moves once
	•	each state is solved once
	•	each operation touches only a log-height path
	•	each query reuses preprocessing
	•	each element’s expensive operation can only happen a bounded number of times

That is the essence.

⸻

10) Final compression

If I compress the whole Opt Complexity layer into one sentence:

Draw the smallest proof that every important unit of work has a bounded lifetime.

That is how to draw optimized complexity across the whole corpus.

