12) How much to draw

This is one of the biggest quality rules.

Draw enough to explain the algorithm, but not enough to recreate the whole program.

That means:

Draw:
	•	critical input structure
	•	important parameters
	•	active variables
	•	helper structures
	•	answer location

Do not draw:
	•	every loop counter if only one matters
	•	every element if only a few matter
	•	every recursive call if state table is cleaner
	•	full giant hash map when 3 entries show the pattern
	•	every table row when 3 are enough

The best diagrams are selective, not exhaustive.

⸻

13) The variable hierarchy rule

When in doubt, draw variables in this priority order:

Highest priority
	•	variables that define state
	•	variables that move
	•	variables that control correctness

Examples:
	•	L, R
	•	curr
	•	dist
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	carry

Medium priority
	•	variables that store answer progress

Examples:
	•	best
	•	ans
	•	count

Lower priority
	•	variables that are code-local but visually unimportant

Examples:
	•	tiny temporary loop values
	•	helper counters that do not change reasoning

If a variable does not change the mental model, skip it.

⸻

14) The invariant label rule

Every strong diagram should have one short invariant sentence.

Examples:
	•	Window contains no duplicates
	•	Stack is decreasing
	•	dp[i] = best answer up to i
	•	Visited cells will not be re-entered
	•	Heap top is smallest active candidate
	•	Map stores counts inside current window

This turns variables from random labels into a coherent machine.

⸻

15) The universal template

For any question, fill this out before drawing:

Input

What structure is given?
________________

Parameters

What extra values are given?
________________

Live variables

What changes during execution?
________________

Helper structures

What is maintained externally?
________________

Output

What form does the answer take?
________________

Invariant

What must remain true?
________________

That is enough to design the whole visual.

⸻

16) The most common mistakes

Mistake 1

Drawing variables detached from the objects they control.

Mistake 2

Using too many variable labels.

Mistake 3

Not separating input from helper state.

Mistake 4

Not showing where the output comes from.

Mistake 5

Not labeling the meaning of DP/map/state structures.

Mistake 6

Drawing code syntax instead of data/state.

⸻

17) The deepest one-line rule

Draw variables where they live, not where they are declared in code.

That is the best compression of this whole guide.

Because a variable is meaningful only when the viewer can see:
	•	what it points to,
	•	what it summarizes,
	•	what it controls,
	•	or what it returns.

⸻

18) Final compression

If I compress the whole guide into one sentence:

Draw the input as the world, draw the variables as the live control state inside that world, draw the helper structures beside it, and draw the output where the answer emerges.

That is how to draw input, output, variables, and state for essentially any question.

