HOW TO DRAW CONSTRAINTS


Yes — constraints need their own visual layer.

Most people treat constraints as text at the top of the problem and then ignore them.
In a strong visual system, constraints are not decoration. They are the physics panel of the problem.

Deep rule

Constraints should be drawn as budgets and limits, not as plain notes.

That means a good constraints drawing answers:
	•	how big can the input get?
	•	how fast can the solution afford to be?
	•	how much memory can it spend?
	•	what values or edge conditions matter?
	•	what solution families are ruled out?

So the right mental model is:

Constraints drawing = budget box + danger flags + allowed complexity zone

⸻

1) What constraints really are

Constraints are not just numbers like:
	•	1 <= n <= 10^5
	•	-10^9 <= nums[i] <= 10^9
	•	grid.length <= 200
	•	“the answer fits in 32-bit integer”

They define:

A. Size budget

How much data exists?

B. Time budget

What time complexity is realistic?

C. Space budget

How much memory is safe?

D. Value domain

How large/small can numbers or symbols be?

E. Structural restrictions

Sorted? Unique? Binary tree? Connected graph? No cycles? Lowercase letters only?

F. Edge-case triggers

Empty? Single element? Negative values? Duplicates? Overflow risk?

So constraints are the physical law layer of the problem.

⸻

2) The 6 kinds of constraints you should draw

1. Input size constraints

Examples:
	•	n <= 20
	•	n <= 10^3
	•	n <= 10^5
	•	m, n <= 200

These determine what runtimes are affordable.

2. Value constraints

Examples:
	•	nums[i] <= 10^9
	•	values may be negative
	•	lowercase English letters only
	•	weights are 0 or 1

These affect:
	•	overflow
	•	hashing/count arrays
	•	binary search range
	•	bit tricks
	•	alphabet-size optimization

3. Shape constraints

Examples:
	•	sorted array
	•	BST
	•	DAG
	•	connected graph
	•	matrix dimensions fixed
	•	linked list length bounded

These affect which patterns are legal or likely.

4. Operation/query constraints

Examples:
	•	up to 10^5 queries
	•	many updates + many range queries
	•	online operations
	•	API called many times

These often force preprocessing, heaps, segment trees, or amortized designs.

5. Output constraints

Examples:
	•	answer fits in 32-bit integer
	•	return all solutions
	•	lexicographically smallest answer
	•	must be in-place

These affect memory, tie-breaking, and design choices.

6. Hidden practical constraints

Examples:
	•	recursion depth risk
	•	stack overflow risk
	•	repeated string copying too costly
	•	too many temporary objects

These are not always explicit, but you should still draw them when relevant.

⸻

3) The 4 main ways to draw constraints

There are four strong visual styles.

⸻

Style A — Constraint summary box

This is the default style.

Draw

A small box near the input with items like:
	•	n <= 10^5
	•	values up to 10^9
	•	duplicates allowed
	•	sorted = no
	•	memory: extra O(n) okay

Best for

Almost every problem.

Use when

You want a compact problem header.

Example

Constraints
n <= 10^5
-10^9 <= nums[i] <= 10^9
duplicates allowed

This is the simplest and most universal.

⸻

Style B — Complexity budget ladder

This is the most important style for algorithm selection.

Draw

A small ladder or filter chart:
	•	n <= 20 → exponential okay
	•	n <= 10^3 → quadratic maybe okay
	•	n <= 10^5 → need O(n) / O(n log n)
	•	huge range → think binary search / math

Best for

Interview explanation, taxonomy pages, problem diagnosis visuals.

Why it matters

This visually turns constraints into allowed engine space.

⸻

Style C — Danger flags / hazard icons

Use this when a constraint changes the solution style sharply.

Draw flags like:
	•	negative values
	•	duplicates
	•	overflow risk
	•	weighted edges
	•	online queries
	•	many operations
	•	lowercase alphabet only

Best for

Problems where one detail changes everything.

Example:
	•	shortest path + weighted edges = BFS may fail
	•	duplicates in binary search = boundary variant
	•	lowercase only = count array possible
	•	answer must be in-place = extra-space solutions demoted

⸻

Style D — Range bars / domain strips

Use this when the numeric/value range itself matters.

Draw
	•	number lines
	•	small interval bars
	•	label ranges like [1, 10^9]
	•	value domain boxes like chars in [a-z]

Best for
	•	answer-space binary search
	•	overflow-sensitive math
	•	bounded alphabets
	•	coordinate ranges
	•	divisor/bit problems

⸻

4) The universal constraints layout

The cleanest placement is:

Top-left or top-right of the diagram:

Constraint Panel

This panel should usually contain:

A. Size
	•	n
	•	m x n
	•	V, E
	•	query count

B. Value domain
	•	range of values
	•	negatives?
	•	duplicates?
	•	weighted?
	•	alphabet size?

C. Implication

One line saying what this means:
	•	“quadratic too slow”
	•	“BFS valid (unweighted)”
	•	“count array possible”
	•	“need O(n log n) or better”

That last line is the most important.

⸻

5) How to draw constraints for different problem families

⸻

A. Arrays / Strings

Draw

Constraint box with:
	•	n <= ...
	•	value/char domain
	•	sorted or unsorted
	•	duplicates yes/no

Add implication strip

Examples:
	•	n <= 10^5 → no O(n^2)
	•	lowercase letters only → count array / freq[26] possible
	•	sorted input → two pointers / binary search possible

Best visual

Input strip plus small constraint box above it.

⸻

B. Sliding window / substring problems

Draw
	•	string strip
	•	constraint box:
	•	|s| <= 10^5
	•	lowercase letters only
	•	contiguous substring required

Add implication note
	•	“Need O(n) or O(n log n)”
	•	“Alphabet bounded → freq array possible”

This helps explain why window + count array or hash map is natural.

⸻

C. Graph / tree / grid problems

Draw

Constraint box with:
	•	V, E
	•	m x n
	•	weighted/unweighted
	•	connected/disconnected
	•	DAG or not

Add danger flags
	•	weighted edges
	•	cycles
	•	multiple sources
	•	sparse vs dense

Implication note

Examples:
	•	unweighted shortest path → BFS viable
	•	weighted shortest path → Dijkstra/0-1 BFS
	•	DAG → topo/DP possible
	•	grid <= 200 x 200 → O(MN) okay

This is one of the most important uses of constraints drawing.

⸻

D. DP problems

Draw

Constraint box with:
	•	dimensions of state candidates
	•	e.g. n <= 1000, m <= 1000
	•	or n <= 200
	•	or sum <= 10^4

Add state-budget note

Examples:
	•	dp[n][n] okay if n <= 500
	•	dp[n][sum] okay only if sum is small
	•	bitmask DP okay if n <= 20

Best visual

Constraint box + quick state table estimate:
	•	states ≈ n
	•	states ≈ n^2
	•	states ≈ 2^n

That is extremely useful.

⸻

E. Binary search on answer

Draw
	•	answer range bar [low, high]
	•	constraint box with:
	•	item count
	•	candidate range
	•	checker cost

Add implication

Example:
	•	n <= 10^5, answer range <= 10^9
	•	checker O(n)
	•	total okay: O(n log 10^9)

This is the cleanest way to visually justify answer-space search.

⸻

F. Design / API problems

Draw

Constraint box with:
	•	number of operations
	•	performance per operation required
	•	allowed extra memory
	•	online nature

Add implication

Examples:
	•	10^5 calls → each op must be ~O(1) or O(log n)
	•	online updates → preprocessing alone is insufficient
	•	“design data structure” → per-call performance matters more than one-time cost

⸻

G. SQL / table problems

Draw

Constraint box with:
	•	row counts if known
	•	uniqueness of keys
	•	nulls allowed
	•	grouping/join semantics

Add implication

Examples:
	•	unique IDs → simple join
	•	duplicates → grouping/windowing may matter
	•	null preservation → left join semantics

⸻

6) The most useful visual: constraints → allowed complexity

This is the single strongest constraint drawing.

Draw a mini filter like this:

Complexity filter
	•	n <= 20 → exponential possible
	•	n <= 200 → cubic maybe possible
	•	n <= 10^3 → quadratic okay sometimes
	•	n <= 10^5 → linear / n log n preferred
	•	n very large / answer range huge → logarithmic or formula methods

This is not exact law, but it is the most useful practical visual.

You can place this beside the raw problem constraint.

⸻

7) How constraints connect to the rest of the diagram

Constraints should connect to:

Input

Example:
	•	n <= 10^5 attached to array
	•	m,n <= 200 attached to grid
	•	V,E attached to graph

Pattern choice

Example:
	•	“sorted” arrow to binary search / two pointers
	•	“lowercase only” arrow to count array
	•	“weighted” arrow away from plain BFS
	•	n <= 20 arrow to backtracking / bitmask

Complexity box

Example:
	•	“No O(n^2)”
	•	“Need O(V+E)”
	•	“Need O(1)/O(log n) per operation”

This is the right integration.

