11) Common mistakes when drawing constraints

Mistake 1

Copying the raw constraints text without showing what it implies.

Bad:
n <= 10^5

Better:
n <= 10^5  ->  no O(n^2), prefer O(n)/O(n log n)

Mistake 2

Forgetting value constraints.

These often matter for:
	•	overflow
	•	count arrays
	•	answer-space search
	•	bit tricks
	•	divisors

Mistake 3

Not marking structural constraints.

Examples:
	•	sorted
	•	DAG
	•	BST
	•	unique
	•	weighted/unweighted

These are high-signal.

Mistake 4

Not connecting constraints to algorithm choice.

Constraints should not be isolated decoration.

