how to draw edge cases / assumptions / invariants together as a “correctness panel.”


how to draw edge cases / assumptions / invariants together as a “correctness pane





Yes — this is the right next layer.

A correctness panel is where you stop drawing only the algorithm’s movement and start drawing the logic that keeps it valid.

The clean idea is:

Correctness panel = edge cases + assumptions + invariant

It should answer three questions:
	•	What inputs can break me? → edge cases
	•	What am I allowed to rely on? → assumptions
	•	What must stay true throughout execution? → invariant

That panel is the “why this doesn’t break” part of the diagram.

⸻

1) What each piece means

Edge cases

These are the weird or small inputs that often break logic.

Examples:
	•	empty array
	•	one element
	•	all equal values
	•	all negative values
	•	duplicates
	•	already sorted
	•	no valid answer
	•	root is null
	•	graph disconnected
	•	single row / single column
	•	overflow boundaries

These are failure triggers.

⸻

Assumptions

These are facts the algorithm is allowed to trust.

Examples:
	•	input is sorted
	•	graph is unweighted
	•	tree is a BST
	•	values fit in 32-bit signed int
	•	characters are lowercase English letters only
	•	exactly one answer exists
	•	there are no self-loops
	•	list is non-empty

These are legal premises.

⸻

Invariant

This is the rule that stays true after every update.

Examples:
	•	current window is valid
	•	prefix before i is already processed
	•	stack is monotonic
	•	queue holds current BFS layer
	•	heap top is best active candidate
	•	dp[i] means best answer up to i
	•	visited cells will not be re-entered
	•	subtree return value is correct before combining

This is the correctness backbone.

⸻

2) Why group them together?

Because together they form a complete correctness story:
	•	assumptions tell you what the problem guarantees,
	•	edge cases tell you what can still break naive logic,
	•	invariants tell you why the algorithm remains correct despite updates.

So a correctness panel is really:

premises + danger zones + unbreakable rule

⸻

3) The best layout

Use a small side panel, usually on the right or bottom-right of the main diagram.

Recommended structure

Correctness Panel

Assumptions
	•	sorted input
	•	lowercase letters only
	•	nonnegative weights

Edge Cases
	•	empty input
	•	duplicate values
	•	no solution
	•	single node

Invariant
	•	window contains at most k distinct chars

That is the cleanest default.

⸻

4) The 3 visual styles

Style A — Boxed checklist

Best general-purpose style.

Draw one box split into 3 sections:
	•	Assumptions
	•	Edge Cases
	•	Invariant

Use for almost every problem.

⸻

Style B — Traffic-light panel

Use when you want stronger visual separation.
	•	Green = assumptions / safe facts
	•	Red = edge cases / danger
	•	Blue or bold = invariant / control law

Even without color, you can use icons:
	•	✓ assumptions
	•	⚠ edge cases
	•	★ invariant

⸻

Style C — Inline callouts

Use when one condition belongs directly to the object.

Examples:
	•	“sorted” written above the array
	•	“duplicates allowed” near the input
	•	“window valid” next to [L, R]
	•	“root may be null” next to the tree
	•	“weights are 0/1” next to graph edges

This works well when the panel would be too detached.

⸻

5) What to draw for each section

Assumptions

Draw them as badges or premise labels.

Examples:
	•	Sorted
	•	BST
	•	DAG
	•	Lowercase only
	•	Unweighted
	•	Unique answer
	•	Non-empty

These should feel stable and trusted.

Good placements
	•	above the input
	•	in the correctness panel
	•	attached to the structure they constrain

⸻

Edge cases

Draw them as hazard flags.

Examples:
	•	n = 0
	•	n = 1
	•	all duplicates
	•	all negatives
	•	null root
	•	disconnected
	•	overflow risk
	•	no valid path

These should feel like “test this before trusting the machine.”

Good placements
	•	inside the correctness panel
	•	near the input boundary
	•	next to fragile variables like mid, carry, head

⸻

Invariant

Draw it as the main law sentence.

This should almost always be one short sentence.

Examples:
	•	Window is always valid
	•	Stack stays decreasing
	•	All nodes in queue are current layer
	•	dp[i] is optimal for prefix i
	•	Processed prefix is finalized
	•	Visited cells are not re-entered

This should be the most prominent line in the panel.

Good placement

Closest to the active state.

Because the invariant belongs to the machine, not just the problem statement.

⸻

6) The universal correctness-panel template

For any question, fill this in:

Assumptions

What facts can I trust from the prompt?
	•	________________
	•	________________

Edge Cases

What small or weird inputs could break naive logic?
	•	________________
	•	________________

Invariant

What must remain true after every update?
	•	________________

That is enough for almost every problem.

⸻

7) How to build the panel by problem type

A. Arrays / Strings

Assumptions
	•	sorted / unsorted
	•	duplicates allowed
	•	lowercase only
	•	contiguous matters

Edge cases
	•	empty
	•	single element
	•	all same chars
	•	no answer
	•	negative numbers if sum/window logic depends on sign

Invariants
	•	current window valid
	•	processed prefix finalized
	•	left side < target / right side > target
	•	prefix sum map stores all previous states

⸻

B. Linked Lists

Assumptions
	•	singly or doubly linked
	•	head may be null
	•	list length constraints

Edge cases
	•	empty list
	•	one node
	•	cycle
	•	even/odd length
	•	tail handling
	•	head replacement

Invariants
	•	prev points to reversed prefix
	•	dummy head always anchors result
	•	slow/fast maintain relative speed
	•	tail points to built list

⸻

C. Trees

Assumptions
	•	BST or plain tree
	•	binary or N-ary
	•	root may be null

Edge cases
	•	null root
	•	leaf node
	•	skewed tree
	•	duplicate values if BST semantics matter

Invariants
	•	subtree return is correct
	•	traversal order has processed required children first
	•	recursion respects tree structure

⸻

D. Graphs / BFS / DFS

Assumptions
	•	weighted or unweighted
	•	directed or undirected
	•	connected or disconnected
	•	DAG or not

Edge cases
	•	isolated node
	•	disconnected graph
	•	cycles
	•	source equals target
	•	zero edges

Invariants
	•	visited prevents repeats
	•	queue stores current shortest-distance frontier
	•	indegree zero means ready
	•	popped Dijkstra node has final shortest distance

⸻

E. Grid / Matrix

Assumptions
	•	4-dir or 8-dir movement
	•	rectangular grid
	•	obstacles meaning fixed

Edge cases
	•	1x1 grid
	•	all blocked
	•	all open
	•	border cells only
	•	no path

Invariants
	•	visited cells are settled
	•	current frontier is one BFS layer
	•	dp cell depends only on solved neighbors

⸻

F. DP

Assumptions
	•	state meaning is well-defined
	•	transition uses smaller/earlier states
	•	base cases exist

Edge cases
	•	smallest size
	•	impossible state
	•	zero target
	•	negative/overflow if relevant
	•	empty prefix

Invariants
	•	every computed state has exact meaning
	•	dependencies are solved before use
	•	memoized state is computed once

⸻

G. Greedy

Assumptions
	•	local-choice rule is valid
	•	sorting order is meaningful
	•	exchange argument exists

Edge cases
	•	ties
	•	equal endpoints/values
	•	empty active set
	•	impossible completion

Invariants
	•	all processed items satisfy the greedy condition
	•	chosen partial solution is still extendable optimally

Greedy panels should often include a note like:
“Assumption: local best choice is safe.”

⸻

H. Binary Search

Assumptions
	•	search space is ordered or monotone
	•	feasibility flips only once

Edge cases
	•	duplicates
	•	target absent
	•	boundary at ends
	•	overflow in mid
	•	empty range

Invariants
	•	answer is still inside [lo, hi]
	•	left side impossible / right side possible
	•	or equivalent boundary invariant

This is one of the best places for a correctness panel.

⸻

I. Design / API

Assumptions
	•	operation semantics fixed
	•	methods may be called many times
	•	object state persists

Edge cases
	•	empty structure
	•	eviction on size 0/1
	•	repeated identical operations
	•	partial buffer
	•	stale entries

Invariants
	•	map and linked list stay synchronized
	•	buffer stores unread leftovers
	•	internal ordering reflects the required policy

⸻

8) The “panel strength” rule

Not all three sections need equal size.

If assumptions dominate

Make the assumptions section bigger.

Example:
	•	binary search
	•	graph shortest path
	•	BST problems

If edge cases dominate

Make the edge-case section bigger.

Example:
	•	linked lists
	•	parsing
	•	integer overflow
	•	null-heavy tree logic

If invariant dominates

Make the invariant the biggest part.

Example:
	•	sliding window
	•	DP
	•	monotonic stack
	•	heap / Dijkstra
	•	greedy

So the panel should match the problem’s fragility.

⸻

9) The decision tree for choosing panel emphasis

Q1. Does the algorithm rely on a strong premise from the input?

Examples:
	•	sorted
	•	BST
	•	DAG
	•	unweighted
	•	lowercase alphabet
	•	exactly one answer

Yes

Emphasize:

Assumptions

⸻

Q2. Is the algorithm easy in general but fragile on tiny/weird inputs?

Examples:
	•	linked lists
	•	binary search boundaries
	•	empty structures
	•	overflow-sensitive math

Yes

Emphasize:

Edge Cases

⸻

Q3. Is the algorithm’s correctness mainly about maintaining a live condition?

Examples:
	•	sliding window
	•	stack
	•	heap
	•	DP
	•	BFS layer logic
	•	greedy partial correctness

Yes

Emphasize:

Invariant

⸻

Q4. Are all three important?

Examples:
	•	binary search
	•	graph shortest path
	•	design questions
	•	DP with special base cases

Yes

Use:

Balanced full panel

