	1.	show object internal state before call
	2.	show one API call entering
	3.	show local state mutation
	4.	show return value and new object state

⸻

9) What a frame should literally contain

A complete frame should usually include:
	•	Frame number
	•	Trigger
	•	Main world
	•	Changed variables
	•	Helper structure snapshot
	•	Invariant
	•	Answer / output status

That is the minimum consistent storyboard format.

⸻

10) The best frame labels

Use short labels like:
	•	Initialize
	•	Expand
	•	Shrink
	•	Push
	•	Pop
	•	Visit
	•	Relax
	•	Merge
	•	Fill
	•	Rewire
	•	Update Answer
	•	Finalize

These work much better than long code-style descriptions.

⸻

11) How to highlight change

This is critical.

A dry run only works if the viewer can instantly see what changed.

Use one or more of these:

A. Bold or outlined changed item

Good for:
	•	new pointer position
	•	new cell
	•	new answer

B. Old → new text

Good for:
	•	sum: 8 -> 13
	•	best: 4 -> 5

C. Faded old state + bright new state

Good for:
	•	queue layers
	•	graph frontiers
	•	list links

D. Cross-out removed state

Good for:
	•	popped stack item
	•	removed queue front
	•	invalid candidate discarded

E. Color/state mark

Good for:
	•	visited cells
	•	settled nodes
	•	finished intervals/groups

The viewer should never have to “hunt” for the change.

⸻

12) The invariant lane

A very strong storyboard trick is to keep an invariant lane across all frames.

Example:

Invariant: current window is valid

This appears in the same place every frame.

If the invariant temporarily breaks, show:
	•	window invalid
then the next frame:
	•	window valid again

This is incredibly useful for teaching why the algorithm’s updates are safe.

⸻

13) The answer lane

The answer also deserves a stable place.

Keep:
	•	best
	•	ans
	•	count
	•	result
	•	final order
	•	return value

in the same spot across all frames.

That way the viewer can track:
	•	whether answer changed,
	•	and when it became final.

⸻

14) The storyboard timing rule

Every dry run has three possible clocks:

A. Iteration clock

One frame per loop iteration.

Good for:
	•	simple pointer scans
	•	DP fills
	•	BFS layers

B. Event clock

One frame per meaningful event.

Good for:
	•	stack pops
	•	answer-space checks
	•	design/API problems
	•	branch decisions

C. Layer clock

One frame per level/layer/phase.

Good for:
	•	BFS
	•	preprocessing vs query
	•	sort-then-sweep
	•	recursion phases

Choose the clock that best matches the algorithm’s logic.

⸻

15) Common mistakes

Mistake 1

Making the dry run a code trace.

That is too low-level.

Mistake 2

Changing the diagram layout every frame.

That destroys continuity.

Mistake 3

Not showing the invariant.

Then the frames feel like random motion.

Mistake 4

Showing too many tiny updates in one frame.

This hides causality.

Mistake 5

Omitting helper structures during the run.
Many optimized solutions make no sense without them.

⸻

16) The universal storyboard template

Use this exact master format:

Frame k

Trigger: __________

World: main canvas stays fixed

State:
	•	variables: __________
	•	helper structure: __________

Change: old -> new

Invariant: __________

Answer: __________

That is the best general-purpose dry-run format.

⸻

17) The deepest one-line rule

A dry run should show the algorithm’s state changing in the smallest number of frames needed to make the invariant believable.

That is the best compression.

Because the whole point of a storyboard is not to prove every line of code.
It is to make the transition logic obvious and trustworthy.

⸻

18) Final compression

If I compress the whole guide into one sentence:

Use a stable world, show one meaningful state change per frame, keep the invariant and answer in fixed lanes, and let the viewer see exactly how the machine evolves from input to output.

That is how to draw dry runs, iteration frames, and execution snapshots in a consistent storyboard format.

