Yes — here is a full symbol / notation system for all your algorithm drawings.

The goal is consistency.

A viewer should be able to look at any diagram and instantly know:
	•	what is input
	•	what is live state
	•	what is helper memory
	•	what changed
	•	what is finalized
	•	what is invalid
	•	what is output
	•	what rule/invariant is being enforced

So the deepest rule is:

Same meaning = same symbol every time

That is how a visual system becomes readable.

⸻

1) The master visual grammar

Every diagram object should belong to one of these roles:

Role 1 — Input

What the problem gives you.

Role 2 — Active state

What the algorithm is currently manipulating.

Role 3 — Helper structure

What the algorithm maintains to avoid repeated work.

Role 4 — Processed / finalized state

What is done and will not be revisited.

Role 5 — Output / answer

What the algorithm is building or returning.

Role 6 — Invalid / rejected / popped / dead state

What the algorithm has discarded.

Role 7 — Invariant / explanation

What text explains why the machine is correct.

Everything in the notation system exists to make these roles visually distinct.

⸻

2) The shape system

Use shape before color. Color is optional; shape should carry the meaning even in black and white.

Rectangle

Use for:
	•	arrays
	•	strings
	•	scalar boxes
	•	DP cells
	•	maps/tables
	•	result boxes
	•	process blocks

This is the default general-purpose shape.

Rounded rectangle

Use for:
	•	helper structures
	•	state summary boxes
	•	invariant boxes
	•	answer boxes

This makes “control/state” feel softer than raw input.

Circle

Use for:
	•	graph nodes
	•	tree nodes
	•	state-machine states

Diamond

Use for:
	•	branch decision
	•	feasibility check
	•	yes/no condition
	•	binary-search predicate

Hexagon or double-outlined box

Use for:
	•	canonical theorem/state meaning
	•	especially important invariant
	•	“this is the answer” final box

Bracket / interval marker

Use for:
	•	ranges
	•	windows
	•	active substrings/subarrays
	•	partitions

Table

Use for:
	•	SQL/dataframe views
	•	frequency maps
	•	adjacency lists
	•	memo/dp matrices

⸻

3) Border styles and what they mean

Borders are one of the strongest parts of the system.

Solid thin border

Default neutral object.

Use for:
	•	input elements
	•	inactive but relevant state

Solid bold border

Currently active / updated now.

Use for:
	•	current node
	•	current DP cell
	•	current interval
	•	current frontier
	•	current answer update

Dashed border

Derived/helper/secondary structure.

Use for:
	•	hash map
	•	prefix array
	•	memo table
	•	visited set
	•	support notes

Double border

Final / confirmed / returned / settled.

Use for:
	•	final answer
	•	finalized node
	•	finished interval merge
	•	settled shortest distance
	•	completed output structure

Dotted border

Optional / hypothetical / candidate / not yet committed.

Use for:
	•	speculative midpoint
	•	candidate answer in binary search
	•	branch possibility
	•	future state not yet chosen

Crossed border or X overlay

Invalid / rejected / removed / dead.

Use for:
	•	popped stack element
	•	rejected interval
	•	invalid branch
	•	failed candidate
	•	deleted row/state

⸻

4) Fill / highlight system

Even without color names, you need fill meaning.

No fill

Neutral input or structure.

Light fill

Currently relevant but not changing this exact frame.

Dark fill or bold highlight

Changed this frame / active now.

Faded fill

Already processed or background context.

Pattern fill (stripes / dots)

Special semantic overlays:
	•	visited
	•	blocked
	•	repeated state
	•	memoized
	•	danger / edge case
	•	answer-space candidate

Recommended meanings
	•	striped = blocked / unavailable
	•	dotted = visited / memoized / cached
	•	diagonal slash = invalid / rejected
	•	checker/pulse = active frontier / current layer

⸻

5) Arrow system

Arrows are the verbs of the drawing language.

5.1 Directional motion arrow

Use for:
	•	pointer movement
	•	scan progression
	•	traversal direction
	•	recursion descent
	•	sweep-line motion

Style:
	•	solid arrow

Meaning:
“this moves”

Examples:
	•	L ->
	•	R ->
	•	sweep line from left to right
	•	BFS wave direction

⸻

5.2 State-update arrow

Use for:
	•	old value to new value
	•	one box updates another
	•	recurrence relation
	•	answer update

Style:
	•	solid arrow with label

Examples:
	•	sum -> sum + nums[i]
	•	dp[i-1] -> dp[i]
	•	dist[u] + w -> dist[v]

Meaning:
“this contributes to that update”

⸻

5.3 Dependency arrow

Use for:
	•	DP predecessors
	•	graph relaxation relation
	•	formula dependency
	•	subtree return usage

Style:
	•	thin arrow, usually labeled if helpful

Meaning:
“this is used to compute that”

⸻

5.4 Pointer arrow

Use for:
	•	linked list pointers
	•	tree child links
	•	current variable pointing at a node/index/cell

Style:
	•	label attached to arrow: curr, prev, next, head, tail

Meaning:
“variable references this location”

⸻

5.5 Transition arrow

Use for:
	•	graph/state-machine transitions
	•	trie character transitions
	•	automata edges
	•	recursion branch choices

Style:
	•	labeled arrow if condition matters

Meaning:
“algorithm can move along this edge”

⸻

5.6 Collapse/merge arrow

Use for:
	•	merge intervals
	•	group rows into aggregate
	•	union-find merge
	•	convert input into grouped summary

Style:
	•	multiple arrows converging

Meaning:
“many items become one summarized state”

⸻

5.7 Expansion arrow

Use for:
	•	BFS frontier spread
	•	recursion branching
	•	candidate expansion
	•	interval widening
	•	window expansion

Style:
	•	one-to-many arrows

Meaning:
“one state generates many next states”

⸻

5.8 Return arrow

Use for:
	•	recursion bubbling up
	•	subtree result returning to parent
	•	DFS return values

Style:
	•	upward or reverse arrow, often curved

Meaning:
“computed information returns upward”

⸻

6) Pointer notation system

Pointers and variable references need absolute consistency.

Pointer labels

Always use:
	•	L, R
	•	i, j
	•	mid
	•	curr, prev, next
	•	head, tail
	•	root
	•	u, v for graph nodes if needed

How to draw them

Place the label next to the arrow, not floating elsewhere.

Bad:
L = 3 in a corner with no visual anchor

Good:
L arrow directly pointing at index 3

Pointer movement notation

Use one of:
	•	L ->
	•	R <-
	•	curved arrow from old to new position
	•	old pointer faded, new pointer bold

Two-pointer standard

Use:
	•	opposite ends: L from left, R from right
	•	same direction: L behind R
	•	fast/slow: slow, fast, with different arrow styles if helpful

Midpoint

Use a vertical divider or a labeled pointer:
	•	mid
	•	or a bold center bar

⸻

7) Box-type system

7.1 Input box

Plain rectangle, thin border.

Examples:
	•	array cell
	•	string char box
	•	scalar parameter

7.2 State box

Rounded rectangle, medium border.

Examples:
	•	sum
	•	count
	•	carry
	•	best

7.3 Helper box

Dashed rounded rectangle.

Examples:
	•	map
	•	set
	•	queue
	•	stack
	•	heap
	•	memo table

7.4 Invariant box

Rounded rectangle with double or bold border.

Examples:
	•	Window valid
	•	Stack decreasing
	•	dp[i] = best score up to i

7.5 Answer box

Double border or bold rounded rectangle.

Examples:
	•	ans = 5
	•	result = [2, 7]
	•	return root

7.6 Warning box

Box with warning icon or striped edge.

Examples:
	•	n = 0
	•	overflow risk
	•	graph may be disconnected

⸻

8) Text label system

Text labels should also be standardized.

8.1 Title labels

Use for:
	•	Input
	•	Helper State
	•	Invariant
	•	Answer
	•	Constraints
	•	Correctness

These are section headers.

8.2 State-definition labels

Use for:
	•	dp[i] = min coins for amount i
	•	dist[v] = shortest known distance
	•	parent[x] = component leader

These are essential when a box/table has abstract meaning.

8.3 Event labels

Use for storyboard frames:
	•	Expand R
	•	Pop smaller elements
	•	Relax edge
	•	Fill dp[3][4]
	•	Move node to front

Keep these short.

8.4 Invariant labels

Always sentence-style, short:
	•	Window has no duplicates
	•	Queue holds current BFS layer
	•	Heap top is smallest active

8.5 Complexity labels

Use simple tags:
	•	O(n)
	•	O(n log n)
	•	each element pushed once
	•	states × transitions

⸻

9) Update marker system

This is critical for dry runs.

9.1 Old -> new

Use for scalar updates:
	•	sum: 8 -> 13
	•	best: 3 -> 5
	•	dist[v]: inf -> 7

9.2 Increment / decrement

Use:
	•	+1
	•	-1
	•	count[a]++
	•	freq[c]--

9.3 Rewire marker

Use:
	•	old arrow faded or dashed
	•	new arrow bold

This is best for linked lists/trees.

9.4 Push/pop marker

Use:
	•	push(x)
	•	pop(x)
	•	cross out popped item

9.5 Layer marker

Use for BFS:
	•	Layer 0
	•	Layer 1
	•	Layer 2

Or annotate cells/nodes with distance.

9.6 Fill marker

Use for DP:
	•	highlight new filled cell
	•	arrow from source cells
	•	value appears inside cell

9.7 Merge marker

Use for grouping intervals/rows/components:
	•	multiple arrows into one merged box

9.8 Jump marker

Use for range/jump structures:
	•	2^k
	•	jump 4
	•	highlighted ladder rung

⸻

10) Fade system

Fading is one of the most powerful consistency tools.

Fully visible

Current active state.

Slightly faded

Relevant context, not active this frame.

Heavily faded

Past state or low-priority context.

Ghosted / outline only

Hypothetical future / candidate / discarded-but-shown-for-reference.

Use fades for
	•	previous pointer positions
	•	already processed nodes/cells
	•	old answer before update
	•	previous BFS layers
	•	non-active intervals
	•	background structure that stays fixed

Rule:
fade old context, highlight new action

⸻

11) Color logic, but safely

Color is helpful, but the system must work without it.

Recommended semantic mapping if color is available:
	•	Neutral gray / plain = input/background
	•	Blue-like emphasis = active current state
	•	Green-like emphasis = finalized / correct / accepted
	•	Yellow-like emphasis = warning / current candidate / caution
	•	Red-like emphasis = invalid / popped / rejected
	•	Purple-like emphasis = helper structure / memo / derived state

But always pair color with:
	•	border style
	•	icon
	•	label
	•	shape

Never rely on color alone.

⸻

12) Symbol system by bucket

Now the practical mapping.

Strip / Pointer

Use:
	•	rectangular cells
	•	pointer arrows L, R, i, j
	•	bracket overlays for active ranges
	•	answer box on side
	•	invariant box under strip

Lookup Table

Use:
	•	input strip on left
	•	dashed table/map on right
	•	current-item arrow into key bucket
	•	optional group-bucket dividers

Grid / Board

Use:
	•	square cells
	•	highlighted active cell/frontier
	•	dotted visited marks
	•	striped blocked cells
	•	distance labels inside cells if BFS

Node-Link

Use:
	•	circles/rectangles for nodes
	•	labeled pointer arrows
	•	faded old links + bold new links
	•	return arrows upward for recursion

Coordinate / Interval

Use:
	•	line segments
	•	bars
	•	sweep line
	•	shaded overlap region
	•	merged block box

Container

Use:
	•	stack = vertical pile
	•	queue = horizontal/vertical lane
	•	deque = lane with both ends marked
	•	heap = small tree or funnel

Relational Table

Use:
	•	header rows
	•	grouped row boxes
	•	join lines
	•	aggregate/result table

State Table / DP

Use:
	•	grid/row cells
	•	dependency arrows
	•	filled/unfilled state contrast
	•	base-case section marked separately

Formula / Invariant

Use:
	•	scalar state boxes
	•	equation arrows
	•	digit columns
	•	carry bubbles
	•	cancellation marks for XOR/parity

Range / Bit-State

Use:
	•	binary string cells
	•	interval hierarchy tree
	•	query coverage shading
	•	jump ladder markers

Graph / State-Network

Use:
	•	circles for states
	•	edge labels
	•	active frontier halo
	•	side queue/heap/indegree table

Object / Process

Use:
	•	big outer object box
	•	labeled internal compartments
	•	operation arrow entering
	•	local touched path highlighted

