14) Notation for time and frames

For storyboard consistency:

Frame label

Use:
	•	Frame 0
	•	Frame 1
	•	Frame 2
	•	Final

Event label

Use:
	•	Trigger: expand R
	•	Trigger: pop top
	•	Trigger: relax edge
	•	Trigger: fill dp[2][3]

Change marker

Use:
	•	old -> new
	•	highlight changed objects only

Stable lanes

Keep:
	•	invariant in same place
	•	answer in same place
	•	helper structure in same place

This makes multi-frame diagrams readable.

⸻

15) Mini style guide for writing labels

Use short labels.

Good:
	•	curr
	•	best
	•	dist
	•	frontier
	•	valid window
	•	sorted prefix

Bad:
	•	long prose floating all over the diagram

Long explanations belong:
	•	in the caption,
	•	or inside a dedicated note box,
not scattered inside the world.

⸻

16) The 10 universal notation rules

Rule 1

Input uses plain shapes.

Rule 2

Active state gets bold border or highlight.

Rule 3

Helper structures use dashed or distinct side containers.

Rule 4

Output uses double border or strong answer box.

Rule 5

Invalid/rejected states get crossed or slashed.

Rule 6

Processed/finalized states get check marks or stable fill.

Rule 7

Motion uses arrows.

Rule 8

Change uses old -> new or highlight delta.

Rule 9

Invariant gets its own steady box.

Rule 10

Same concept = same notation every time.

That is the whole consistency contract.

⸻

17) Common mistakes

Mistake 1

Changing meanings across diagrams.
Example:
	•	dashed box means helper in one diagram, candidate in another

Mistake 2

Using too many box types.
If every box has a different style, the system collapses.

Mistake 3

Using color without structural meaning.
This breaks accessibility and black-and-white readability.

Mistake 4

Making arrows do too many jobs without label.
Use different arrow roles or labels.

Mistake 5

No distinction between active and finalized.
Then time progression becomes unclear.

⸻

18) The universal legend

Every large diagram system should have a tiny reusable legend.

Example:

Legend
Plain box   = input
Bold box    = active/current
Dashed box  = helper structure
Double box  = answer/final
X / slash   = invalid / removed
Solid arrow = motion/update
Thin arrow  = dependency
Curved up   = return flow
✓           = settled/correct
!           = danger/edge case

That one legend can support the whole project.

⸻

19) The deepest one-line rule

Your notation system should let the viewer infer meaning before reading the caption.

That is the strongest compression of everything.

Because once the notation is stable:
	•	boxes tell roles,
	•	arrows tell verbs,
	•	borders tell certainty,
	•	highlights tell recency,
	•	labels tell logic.

Then every diagram becomes faster to read.

⸻

20) Final compression

If I compress the whole symbol/notation guide into one sentence:

Use shape for role, border for status, arrows for action, highlights for change, and labels for meaning — and never let the same visual symbol mean two different things.

That is the full symbol/notation system.

