NOW ABOUT MEMORY VISUALISATION



Yes — memory visualization is its own layer.

So far you built:
	•	How to Draw BF
	•	BF Complexity
	•	How to Draw Opt
	•	Opt Complexity
	•	Input / Output / Variables
	•	Constraints
	•	Correctness panel
	•	Dry-run storyboard
	•	Symbol system

Now the missing layer is:

Memory Visualization

This is where you show:
	•	what exists in memory,
	•	what gets created,
	•	what gets reused,
	•	what gets copied,
	•	what grows,
	•	what is temporary,
	•	and what survives across steps.

The deepest rule is:

Memory visualization should show footprint + lifetime + ownership + growth

That is the full mental model.

⸻

1) What memory visualization is really for

A memory diagram should answer five questions:

A. What memory already exists as input?

Examples:
	•	the given array
	•	the given string
	•	linked nodes already allocated
	•	tree nodes already present
	•	graph adjacency list
	•	input tables

B. What extra memory does the algorithm allocate?

Examples:
	•	hash map
	•	set
	•	queue
	•	heap
	•	stack
	•	visited matrix
	•	DP table
	•	prefix array
	•	parent array
	•	memo cache

C. What memory is temporary?

Examples:
	•	current recursion frame
	•	temporary substring copy
	•	temporary vector
	•	current merged buffer
	•	one heap entry
	•	one simulation state

D. What memory grows with input size?

Examples:
	•	O(n) map
	•	O(mn) DP
	•	recursion depth O(h)
	•	O(2^n) subset storage in bad brute force
	•	output-sized storage

E. What memory can be reused or freed?

Examples:
	•	rolling DP rows
	•	reused buffer
	•	popped stack elements disappear
	•	path list backtracks
	•	temporary nodes are not persisted
	•	pointers reuse existing nodes instead of copying them

That is the point of memory visualization.

⸻

2) The deepest distinction: BF memory vs Opt memory

BF memory visualization

should show:
	•	duplication
	•	rebuilding
	•	candidate explosion
	•	copied substrings/subarrays
	•	full path storage
	•	huge recursion trees
	•	repeated temporary structures

It should make memory waste look ugly.

Opt memory visualization

should show:
	•	minimal live state
	•	helper structure footprint
	•	reusable buffers
	•	compact summaries
	•	shared references
	•	in-place mutation when possible
	•	bounded stack/table size

It should make memory feel controlled.

So the big contrast is:

BF memory = uncontrolled duplication

Opt memory = controlled state footprint

⸻

3) The four dimensions every memory diagram should show

1. Footprint

How much memory exists at one time?

Examples:
	•	3 scalar boxes
	•	one map with n entries
	•	DP grid of size m x n
	•	call stack of depth h

2. Lifetime

How long does each piece survive?

Examples:
	•	one recursion frame lives briefly
	•	memo table persists across full run
	•	queue entries enter and leave
	•	object internals persist across operations

3. Ownership / sharing

Who “owns” or points to what?

Examples:
	•	linked-list nodes reused
	•	tree nodes not copied
	•	map points to indices, not to duplicated data
	•	parent pointers own connectivity structure
	•	buffer retains leftovers

4. Growth law

How memory scales with input size.

Examples:
	•	constant
	•	linear
	•	quadratic
	•	output-proportional
	•	recursion-depth proportional
	•	exponential blowup

A strong memory diagram usually shows at least 2 of these, and ideally all 4.

⸻

4) The universal memory diagram formula

For almost any problem, use this template:

Input memory

What is already given?

Extra memory

What new structures are allocated?

Temporary memory

What appears and disappears during execution?

Output memory

What must be stored as the result?

Growth label

How each part scales:
	•	O(1)
	•	O(n)
	•	O(mn)
	•	O(h)
	•	O(output)
	•	O(2^n)

So the full formula is:

Input + Aux + Temporary + Output + Growth

That is the universal memory visualization grammar.

⸻

5) The 12 major memory-visualization buckets

These cover almost all questions.

⸻

Bucket 1 — Constant-state / O(1) extra memory

When to use

Use this when the algorithm only keeps a few scalars/pointers.

Examples:
	•	sum
	•	best
	•	carry
	•	L, R
	•	prev, curr, next
	•	current min/max

What to draw

Draw:
	•	the input world
	•	2–6 small scalar state boxes beside it

What to emphasize
	•	input is reused directly
	•	no data-size-proportional helper structure
	•	only tiny control state exists

Best label

Extra memory = O(1)

Good examples
	•	two pointers
	•	many greedy scans
	•	reverse linked list
	•	carry-based arithmetic
	•	in-place partitioning

What the picture should prove

The algorithm does not allocate memory that grows with input size.

⸻

Bucket 2 — Linear side table / map / set

When to use

Use this when optimization comes from explicit memory.

Examples:
	•	hash map
	•	set
	•	frequency array
	•	parent array
	•	index map
	•	seen-state board

What to draw

Draw:
	•	input on one side
	•	dashed helper table on the other
	•	items entering the helper table
	•	size label like up to n entries

What to emphasize
	•	memory grows with number of distinct items/states
	•	table persists through run
	•	lookup saves time by spending memory

Best label

Aux memory = O(n) or O(k) or O(alphabet)

Good examples
	•	Two Sum optimized
	•	Group Anagrams
	•	frequency counting
	•	visited sets
	•	parent/index arrays

What the picture should prove

The algorithm externalizes memory instead of rescanning input.

⸻

Bucket 3 — Stack / recursion-frame memory

When to use

Use this when recursion or DFS depth matters.

Examples:
	•	tree recursion
	•	DFS
	•	backtracking
	•	divide and conquer
	•	recursive DP

What to draw

Draw:
	•	a vertical call-stack tower
	•	each frame as a box
	•	top frame highlighted
	•	lower frames faded but still alive

What to emphasize
	•	maximum depth, not total calls over time
	•	each frame stores locals/return address/state
	•	recursion depth may depend on:
	•	tree height
	•	path length
	•	n

Best labels
	•	Stack depth = O(h)
	•	Recursion stack = O(n)
	•	Backtracking path = O(depth)

Good examples
	•	DFS on tree
	•	recursive linked-list problems
	•	N-Queens
	•	recursive permutations
	•	memoized recursion

What the picture should prove

Even if time is large, only the active call chain exists simultaneously.

⸻

Bucket 4 — Path / choice-state memory in backtracking

When to use

Use this when brute force or backtracking stores a current path/combination.

Examples:
	•	permutation path
	•	current subset
	•	current board placement
	•	current string build
	•	recursion path list

What to draw

Draw:
	•	recursion stack
	•	a side path list or partial board
	•	“push choice / pop choice” lifecycle

What to emphasize
	•	current path grows and shrinks
	•	path is temporary
	•	only one active path exists at a time unless all results are stored

Best labels
	•	Current path = O(depth)
	•	Output storage may dominate

Good examples
	•	combinations
	•	subsets
	•	permutations
	•	N-Queens
	•	word search path

What the picture should prove

The active decision path is linear in depth, even when the search tree is huge.

⸻

Bucket 5 — Output-sized memory

When to use

Use this when the result itself dominates memory.

Examples:
	•	return all subsets
	•	return all permutations
	•	return all valid boards
	•	grouped anagram lists
	•	topological order list
	•	merged array/list result

What to draw

Draw:
	•	output box or result bank
	•	many result rows/leaves/buckets
	•	small note that memory is proportional to answer size

What to emphasize
	•	output memory is unavoidable
	•	separate it from auxiliary working memory
	•	many “memory heavy” algorithms are only heavy because output is huge

Best labels
	•	Output = O(answer size)
	•	Aux = O(n), Output may dominate

Good examples
	•	return all subsets
	•	group results
	•	permutations
	•	DFS path listings
	•	SQL grouped output

What the picture should prove

Large memory may be unavoidable because the answer itself is large.

⸻

Bucket 6 — DP table / memo cache memory

When to use

Use this when the algorithm stores many states explicitly.

Examples:
	•	dp[i]
	•	dp[i][j]
	•	memo hash
	•	state table
	•	bitmask table

What to draw

Draw:
	•	a row, grid, or sparse memo board
	•	filled cells highlighted
	•	size label like:
	•	n states
	•	m x n states
	•	2^n states

What to emphasize
	•	each state is stored once
	•	table persists across the algorithm
	•	memory cost is determined by state count

Best labels
	•	Space = O(states)
	•	Memo = O(number of unique states)

Good examples
	•	Coin Change
	•	Edit Distance
	•	House Robber DP
	•	interval DP
	•	memoized DFS
	•	bitmask DP

What the picture should prove

The memory cost is the number of distinct states retained for reuse.

⸻

Bucket 7 — Grid / visited / distance board memory

When to use

Use this when the world itself needs an auxiliary board.

Examples:
	•	visited matrix
	•	distance matrix
	•	2D DP table
	•	obstacle/state overlays
	•	multi-source BFS distances

What to draw

Draw:
	•	the grid
	•	plus a second overlay or side copy:
	•	visited
	•	dist
	•	dp
	•	optionally show in-place marking if no extra board is needed

What to emphasize
	•	board-sized memory can be O(mn)
	•	sometimes input is mutated to reuse the same board
	•	visited/distance tables are persistent helper state

Best labels
	•	Visited = O(mn)
	•	Dist board = O(mn)
	•	In-place marking -> no extra board

Good examples
	•	Number of Islands
	•	Rotting Oranges
	•	shortest path in matrix
	•	2D DP problems

What the picture should prove

Space is proportional to board area unless input itself is reused.

⸻

Bucket 8 — Container footprint memory

When to use

Use this when state is stored in:
	•	stack
	•	queue
	•	deque
	•	heap

What to draw

Draw the container and show:
	•	how many active elements it may hold
	•	whether items enter and leave
	•	whether size is bounded by:
	•	window size
	•	level width
	•	number of candidates
	•	number of unresolved items

What to emphasize
	•	footprint is the live contents, not total pushes over time
	•	heap/queue/stack memory is about max simultaneous occupancy

Best labels
	•	Queue size <= width
	•	Stack size <= n
	•	Heap holds active candidates
	•	Deque size <= window

Good examples
	•	BFS queue
	•	monotonic stack
	•	heap-based selection
	•	sliding-window deque
	•	stack parsers

What the picture should prove

The memory cost is the peak size of the container, not how many total operations happen.

⸻

Bucket 9 — Rebuild / copy / temporary-object memory

When to use

Use this when the algorithm creates temporary structures repeatedly.

Examples:
	•	slicing strings
	•	copying subarrays
	•	rebuilding lists
	•	repeated sort buffers
	•	converting linked list to array
	•	creating temporary merged objects

What to draw

Draw:
	•	input
	•	arrows into temporary copy boxes
	•	old copies fading out
	•	maybe many repeated copies stacked

What to emphasize
	•	temporaries may not persist long, but peak memory can still spike
	•	repeated copy cost is both time and space
	•	this is often the real hidden issue in brute force

Best labels
	•	Temp copy = O(k) each
	•	Repeated copies
	•	Peak memory spikes

Good examples
	•	substring slicing brute force
	•	naive design implementations
	•	list/array conversions
	•	copy-heavy string problems

What the picture should prove

The algorithm wastes memory by repeatedly materializing data that could be referenced or updated in place.

⸻

Bucket 10 — Shared-reference / in-place memory

When to use

Use this when the optimized solution reuses existing structure instead of allocating new memory.

Examples:
	•	reversing a linked list in place
	•	marking array entries negative
	•	using input grid as visited board
	•	rearranging array by swaps
	•	pointer rewiring

What to draw

Draw:
	•	original structure
	•	same structure after mutation
	•	no side copy
	•	small scalar state only

What to emphasize
	•	ownership remains with original structure
	•	no cloned object bank
	•	memory saved by mutation

Best labels
	•	In-place
	•	No extra structure
	•	Reuse input storage

Good examples
	•	reverse linked list
	•	cyclic sort style problems
	•	in-place matrix/array marking
	•	constant-space partitioning

What the picture should prove

The optimized algorithm saves space by reusing the input’s storage as working memory.

⸻

Bucket 11 — Persistent object / cache / buffer memory

When to use

Use this for design problems or repeated API calls.

Examples:
	•	LRU cache
	•	LFU cache
	•	Read4 leftover buffer
	•	iterators
	•	streaming systems
	•	async/process objects

What to draw

Draw:
	•	outer object box
	•	internal compartments:
	•	map
	•	list
	•	buffer
	•	cursor
	•	queue
	•	note what persists across calls

What to emphasize
	•	memory survives between operations
	•	persistent state is the whole point
	•	local temporaries are smaller than the persistent internals

Best labels
	•	Persistent internal state
	•	Map + list
	•	Unread buffer
	•	Cursor position retained

Good examples
	•	LRU Cache
	•	Read4
	•	iterator designs
	•	online API state problems

What the picture should prove

Efficient design depends on preserving the right state across operations rather than recomputing everything.

⸻

Bucket 12 — Compressed / hierarchical memory

When to use

Use this when memory is stored in:
	•	segment tree
	•	Fenwick tree
	•	sparse table
	•	binary lifting table
	•	bitmask
	•	compressed parent structure

What to draw

Draw:
	•	hierarchy of blocks
	•	bitmask rows
	•	jump tables
	•	summarized nodes

What to emphasize
	•	structure stores summaries, not raw repeated ranges
	•	memory is organized hierarchically
	•	compressed state may trade memory for faster queries

Best labels
	•	Hierarchy of summaries
	•	2^k jump table
	•	Compressed subset state
	•	Range summaries

Good examples
	•	segment tree
	•	sparse table
	•	Fenwick tree
	•	binary lifting
	•	bitmask DP

What the picture should prove

Memory is spent on compressed summaries so later work is cheaper.

⸻

6) The universal memory layout

The cleanest standard layout is:

Left/top

Input memory

Center

Active state + helper memory

Right/bottom-right

Output memory / answer

Side

Lifetime or growth labels

Example:
	•	input array on left
	•	map/queue/DP in middle/right
	•	answer box on far right
	•	label: Aux = O(n), Output = O(k)

This keeps memory roles visually separated.

⸻

7) The 7 key questions to ask before drawing memory

1. What memory is already given?

Do not count input as extra memory unless you are explicitly discussing total memory footprint.

2. What memory is allocated by the algorithm?

Map, set, queue, table, recursion, buffer, object internals?

3. What survives across the whole run?

Persistent helper state.

4. What is temporary?

Copies, one frame, one buffer, one popped item, one current path.

5. Can the input be reused in place?

This changes the picture completely.

6. Is output memory unavoidable?

Return-all problems especially.

7. What grows with n?

This determines the space complexity label.

