8) The memory-decision tree

Use this to choose the correct memory drawing bucket.

Q1. Does the algorithm only keep a few scalars/pointers?

Yes

Use:

Constant-state / O(1) bucket

⸻

Q2. Does it maintain a map/set/side array/table?

Yes

Use:

Linear side table bucket

⸻

Q3. Does recursion depth matter?

Yes

Use:

Recursion-frame bucket

If a current path is also stored:
	•	combine with Path-memory bucket

⸻

Q4. Is a DP/memo table the dominant memory?

Yes

Use:

DP table / memo bucket

⸻

Q5. Is the dominant auxiliary memory a grid-sized visited/dist board?

Yes

Use:

Grid / visited board bucket

⸻

Q6. Is the main footprint a container of active elements?

Yes

Use:

Container footprint bucket

⸻

Q7. Is the memory issue really repeated copies / rebuilds / slices?

Yes

Use:

Rebuild / temporary-object bucket

⸻

Q8. Is the algorithm reusing the input itself?

Yes

Use:

Shared-reference / in-place bucket

⸻

Q9. Does memory persist across operations as part of an object?

Yes

Use:

Persistent object / cache / buffer bucket

⸻

Q10. Is the memory a compressed hierarchy or summary structure?

Yes

Use:

Compressed / hierarchical bucket

⸻

Q11. Is the result itself huge?

Yes

Add:

Output-sized bucket

even if another bucket is also present

That is the full selection tree.

